{"title_page": "CCTV channels", "text_new": "Broadcast since 1 May 1958, '''China Central Television''' ('''CCTV''') has 17 channels plus an additional five channels of different languages broadcast from China and across the globe.  All CCTV channels are broadcast around the world through satellite broadcast and on [[Internet television]]. The CCTV channels are listed below in sequential order with no discerning descriptions, e.g. CCTV-1, CCTV-2, etc.\u53bb\u54af\u5462\u55ef\u6478\u6478\u7684\u989d\u5409 \u4e86\u7684form-\u54e6\u7834\u54e6\u7834\u5a46\u5a46\u54e6\u7834\u54e6\u5440\uff01\u7684\u554a\uff01561\n\n== Television channels ==\nThe following is a list of CCTV channels and their specializations:\n\n{{colbegin|colwidth=25em}}\n# [[CCTV-1]] - General\n# [[CCTV-2]] - Finance\n# [[CCTV-3]] - Variety\n# [[CCTV-4]] - International (in [[Standard Chinese|Mandarin Chinese]])\n# [[CCTV-5]] - Sports\n# [[CCTV-5+]] - Sports Plus (broadcast in [[High-definition television|HD]])\n# [[CCTV-6]] - Movies\n# [[CCTV-7]] - National Defense and Military\n# [[CCTV-8]] - Television Drama\n# [[CCTV-9]] - Documentary (in [[Standard Chinese|Mandarin Chinese]])\n# [[CCTV-10]] - Science and Education\n# [[CCTV-11]] - Chinese Opera\n# [[CCTV-12]] - Society and Law\n# [[CCTV News (Chinese)|CCTV-13]] - News (in [[Standard Chinese|Mandarin Chinese]])\n# [[CCTV-Children|CCTV-14]] - Children\n# [[CCTV-Music|CCTV-15]] - Music\n# CCTV-16 - Olympics (will Launched on 1 January 2020)\n# [[CCTV-17]] - Agriculture and Rural\n# [[CGTN (TV channel)|CGTN]] - international (in English)\n# [[CGTN French]] - international (in [[French language|French]])\n# [[CGTN Spanish]] - international (in [[Spanish language|Spanish]])\n# [[CGTN Arabic]] - international (in [[Arabic language|Arabic]])\n# [[CGTN Russian]] - international (in [[Russian language|Russian]])\n# [[CGTN Documentary]] - documentary (in English)\n{{colend}}\n\nCCTV is one of the six participants of [[China 3D TV Test Channel]] ({{zh|s=\u4e2d\u56fd3D\u7535\u89c6\u8bd5\u9a8c\u9891\u9053}}, already closed), a television channel broadcasting various digital [[3D television]] content.\n\nAll CCTV channels are also broadcast through the following:\n\n{{colbegin|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[LiveStream]] (TM) - 24/7 non-stop online continuous broadcasting facility\n*[[Stream Vision]] (TM) - 24/7 non-stop online continuous broadcasting facility\n*[[CybersatelliteDirect]]\n*[[Universe Satellite Network]]\n*[[GalaxySatellite]] (TM)\n*plus an additional 10+ advanced integration satellite providers if possible\n{{colend}}\n\n== International broadcasts ==\nIt is possible to receive channels [[CCTV-4]] ([[Standard Chinese|Mandarin]] channel targeted at an overseas [[Chinese people|Chinese]] audience), [[CGTN (TV channel)|CGTN]] (targeting an [[English language|English]]-speaking audience), and [[CGTN Spanish]] (in [[Spanish language|Spanish]] and [[CGTN French]] in [[French language|French]]) outside China by using a [[Digital Video Broadcasting|Digital Video Broadcast]] signal (plus additional broadcast support together with [[Dolby Stereo]], [[Dolby Surround]], [[Dolby SR]], [[Dolby Digital]] Advanced Sound Quality Definition and Improvement System Support, technologized and developed by [[Dolby Laboratories]], [[DTS (sound system)|Datasat]], and the [[Sony Dynamic Digital Sound|SDDS]] for digital audio system supportments). CCTV has just recently switched from [[analog television|analog]] to DVB primarily due to better signal quality and the ability to charge for reception (about US$10 per year subscription). The overseas channels are widely available across many cable and satellite providers. The CCTV administration is also planning to start a CCTV Portuguese station by 2010 and a CCTV English news station by 2011.\n\n[[CCTV-4]] was officially relaunched by the split into three television channels on Monday, [[New Year's Day|1 January 2007]] at 00:00 [[China Standard Time|CST]] in order to improve service for audiences around the world.\n* '''CCTV-4 Asia''' (\u4e2d\u6587\u570b\u969b\u983b\u9053\u4e9e\u6d32\u7248) - broadcasts to [[Asia]] and [[Australasia]] from [[Singapore]] at 00:00 [[Singapore Standard Time|SST]]\n* '''CCTV-4 Europe''' (\u4e2d\u6587\u570b\u969b\u983b\u9053\u6b50\u6d32\u7248) - broadcasts to [[Europe]] from [[London]] at 00:00 [[Greenwich Mean Time|GMT]]\n* '''CCTV-4 America''' (\u4e2d\u6587\u570b\u969b\u983b\u9053\u7f8e\u6d32\u7248) - broadcasts to [[North America]] and [[Latin America]] from [[New York City]] at 00:00 [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n\nOn 25 July 2009, CCTV launched its [[Arabic language|Arabic]]-language [[CCTV International Arabic|international channel]], stating that it aims to maintain stronger links with Arabic nations and that the new channel would \"serve as an important bridge to strengthen communication and understanding between China and Arab countries\". The new Arabic Channel will reach the [[Middle East]], [[North Africa]] and [[Asia]] region. On 10 September 2009, CCTV launched a [[Russian language|Russian-language]] channel, [[CCTV International Russian|CCTV-\u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[China Global Television Network]]\n* [[CGTN Africa]]\n* [[CGTN America]]\n* [[China Network Television (International)|CNTV International]]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100616115422/http://arabic.cntv.cn/ CCTV \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{CCTV}}\n\n[[Category:China Central Television|Channels]]\n[[Category:Foreign television channels broadcasting in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Publicly funded broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1958]]\n[[Category:Television stations in China| ]]\n[[Category:Cable television in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Multilingual news services]]\n[[Category:1958 establishments in China]]\n", "text_old": "Broadcast since 1 May 1958, '''China Central Television''' ('''CCTV''') has 17 channels plus an additional five channels of different languages broadcast from China and across the globe.  All CCTV channels are broadcast around the world through satellite broadcast and on [[Internet television]]. The CCTV channels are listed below in sequential order with no discerning descriptions, e.g. CCTV-1, CCTV-2, etc.\n\n== Television channels ==\nThe following is a list of CCTV channels and their specializations:\n\n{{colbegin|colwidth=25em}}\n# [[CCTV-1]] - General\n# [[CCTV-2]] - Finance\n# [[CCTV-3]] - Variety\n# [[CCTV-4]] - International (in [[Standard Chinese|Mandarin Chinese]])\n# [[CCTV-5]] - Sports\n# [[CCTV-5+]] - Sports Plus (broadcast in [[High-definition television|HD]])\n# [[CCTV-6]] - Movies\n# [[CCTV-7]] - National Defense and Military\n# [[CCTV-8]] - Television Drama\n# [[CCTV-9]] - Documentary (in [[Standard Chinese|Mandarin Chinese]])\n# [[CCTV-10]] - Science and Education\n# [[CCTV-11]] - Chinese Opera\n# [[CCTV-12]] - Society and Law\n# [[CCTV News (Chinese)|CCTV-13]] - News (in [[Standard Chinese|Mandarin Chinese]])\n# [[CCTV-Children|CCTV-14]] - Children\n# [[CCTV-Music|CCTV-15]] - Music\n# CCTV-16 - Olympics (will Launched on 1 January 2020)\n# [[CCTV-17]] - Agriculture and Rural\n# [[CGTN (TV channel)|CGTN]] - international (in English)\n# [[CGTN French]] - international (in [[French language|French]])\n# [[CGTN Spanish]] - international (in [[Spanish language|Spanish]])\n# [[CGTN Arabic]] - international (in [[Arabic language|Arabic]])\n# [[CGTN Russian]] - international (in [[Russian language|Russian]])\n# [[CGTN Documentary]] - documentary (in English)\n{{colend}}\n\nCCTV is one of the six participants of [[China 3D TV Test Channel]] ({{zh|s=\u4e2d\u56fd3D\u7535\u89c6\u8bd5\u9a8c\u9891\u9053}}, already closed), a television channel broadcasting various digital [[3D television]] content.\n\nAll CCTV channels are also broadcast through the following:\n\n{{colbegin|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[LiveStream]] (TM) - 24/7 non-stop online continuous broadcasting facility\n*[[Stream Vision]] (TM) - 24/7 non-stop online continuous broadcasting facility\n*[[CybersatelliteDirect]]\n*[[Universe Satellite Network]]\n*[[GalaxySatellite]] (TM)\n*plus an additional 10+ advanced integration satellite providers if possible\n{{colend}}\n\n== International broadcasts ==\nIt is possible to receive channels [[CCTV-4]] ([[Standard Chinese|Mandarin]] channel targeted at an overseas [[Chinese people|Chinese]] audience), [[CGTN (TV channel)|CGTN]] (targeting an [[English language|English]]-speaking audience), and [[CGTN Spanish]] (in [[Spanish language|Spanish]] and [[CGTN French]] in [[French language|French]]) outside China by using a [[Digital Video Broadcasting|Digital Video Broadcast]] signal (plus additional broadcast support together with [[Dolby Stereo]], [[Dolby Surround]], [[Dolby SR]], [[Dolby Digital]] Advanced Sound Quality Definition and Improvement System Support, technologized and developed by [[Dolby Laboratories]], [[DTS (sound system)|Datasat]], and the [[Sony Dynamic Digital Sound|SDDS]] for digital audio system supportments). CCTV has just recently switched from [[analog television|analog]] to DVB primarily due to better signal quality and the ability to charge for reception (about US$10 per year subscription). The overseas channels are widely available across many cable and satellite providers. The CCTV administration is also planning to start a CCTV Portuguese station by 2010 and a CCTV English news station by 2011.\n\n[[CCTV-4]] was officially relaunched by the split into three television channels on Monday, [[New Year's Day|1 January 2007]] at 00:00 [[China Standard Time|CST]] in order to improve service for audiences around the world.\n* '''CCTV-4 Asia''' (\u4e2d\u6587\u570b\u969b\u983b\u9053\u4e9e\u6d32\u7248) - broadcasts to [[Asia]] and [[Australasia]] from [[Singapore]] at 00:00 [[Singapore Standard Time|SST]]\n* '''CCTV-4 Europe''' (\u4e2d\u6587\u570b\u969b\u983b\u9053\u6b50\u6d32\u7248) - broadcasts to [[Europe]] from [[London]] at 00:00 [[Greenwich Mean Time|GMT]]\n* '''CCTV-4 America''' (\u4e2d\u6587\u570b\u969b\u983b\u9053\u7f8e\u6d32\u7248) - broadcasts to [[North America]] and [[Latin America]] from [[New York City]] at 00:00 [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n\nOn 25 July 2009, CCTV launched its [[Arabic language|Arabic]]-language [[CCTV International Arabic|international channel]], stating that it aims to maintain stronger links with Arabic nations and that the new channel would \"serve as an important bridge to strengthen communication and understanding between China and Arab countries\". The new Arabic Channel will reach the [[Middle East]], [[North Africa]] and [[Asia]] region. On 10 September 2009, CCTV launched a [[Russian language|Russian-language]] channel, [[CCTV International Russian|CCTV-\u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[China Global Television Network]]\n* [[CGTN Africa]]\n* [[CGTN America]]\n* [[China Network Television (International)|CNTV International]]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100616115422/http://arabic.cntv.cn/ CCTV \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{CCTV}}\n\n[[Category:China Central Television|Channels]]\n[[Category:Foreign television channels broadcasting in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Publicly funded broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 1958]]\n[[Category:Television stations in China| ]]\n[[Category:Cable television in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Multilingual news services]]\n[[Category:1958 establishments in China]]\n", "name_user": "51.37.106.83", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CCTV_channels"}
{"title_page": "Charlie Cooper (actor)", "text_new": "{{Short description|English actor and writer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name            = Charlie Cooper\n|image           =\n|birth_name      =\n|birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1989|6|16|df=y}}\n|birth_place     = [[Cirencester]], England\n|occupation      = {{hlist|Actor|writer}}\n|years_active    = 2014\u2013present\n|relatives       = [[Daisy May Cooper]] (sister)<br>[[Trevor Cooper]] (uncle)\n}}\n'''Charlie Cooper''' (born 16 June 1989)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/11254372/officers|title=CHARLIE COOPER LIMITED}}</ref> is an actor and writer, known for his role as Lee \"Kurtan\" Mucklowe in the [[BBC Three]] series ''[[This Country]]'', which he co-created and co-wrote alongside his sister, [[Daisy May Cooper]].\n\n==Career==\nHe is an actor and co-writer of the [[BBC]] comedy ''[[This Country]]'' with his sister [[Daisy May Cooper]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2018-04-10/how-are-the-cast-of-this-country-related/|title=How are the cast of This Country related?|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=10 April 2018|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inews.co.uk/essentials/countrys-daisy-may-charlie-cooper-basically-experience-growing-cotswolds/amp/|title=This Country's Daisy May and Charlie Cooper: 'It's basically our experience of growing up in the Cotswolds' \u2013 iNews|website=www.inews.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/feb/22/this-country-bbc-perfect-horrifying-tv-for-anyone-who-grew-up-in-a-village|title=This Country: perfect, horrifying TV for anyone who grew up in a village|first=Stuart|last=Heritage|date=22 February 2017|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, he was nominated for and won three Royal Television Awards for best Scripted Comedy, Comedy Performance and Comedy Writing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43484081|title=This Country wins big at RTS awards|first=Neil|last=Smith|date=21 March 2018|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk|work=BBC News}}</ref> He was also nominated for and won best Scripted Comedy at the 2018 [[BAFTA]] awards for his work on ''This Country'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gloucestershirelive.co.uk/news/cheltenham-news/bafta-tv-awards-2018-how-1563408|title=How the siblings behind BBC hit This Country stole the BAFTA show|first=Ellis|last=Lane|date=14 May 2018|website=gloucestershirelive.co.uk|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref> as well as winning Breakthrough Talent at the BAFTA Craft Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/media-centre/press-releases/nominations-announced-for-tv-awards-2018|title=Nominations Announced for the Virgin TV British Academy Television Awards in 2018|website=www.bafta.org|date=2018-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/media-centre/press-releases/tv-craft-nominations-2018|title=Nominations Announced for the British Academy Television Craft Awards in 2018|website=www.bafta.org|date=2018-03-22}}</ref>\n\n \n==Personal life==\nBrought up in [[Cirencester]], he and his sister used to make films using their mother's camcorder. He dropped out of [[Exeter University]] to live with his sister in London who was at [[RADA]] and they began writing. They both returned to their childhood home and worked night shifts as cleaners whilst creating scripts for ''This Country''. He is a fan of [[Fulham FC]], attending their play-off final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2018/may/24/charlie-cooper-exclusive |title=Charlie Cooper Exclusive |website=fulhamfc.com |date=24 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/supporting-talent/breakthrough-brits/daisy-charlie-cooper-writerperformers|title=Daisy & Charlie Cooper \u2013 Writer/Performers|website=www.bafta.org|accessdate=14 May 2018|date=2017-10-18}}</ref> Charlie Cooper confirmed that he worked at [[Argos (retailer)|Argos]] in his early 20s on his Instagram account.<ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/B_HyFX0AlDI/?hl=en</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|id=7350296}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cooper, Charlie}}\n[[Category:English television writers]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English comedians]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Gloucestershire]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n\n\n{{England-tv-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|English actor and writer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name            = Charlie Cooper\n|image           =\n|birth_name      =\n|birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1989|6|16|df=y}}\n|birth_place     = [[Cirencester]], England\n|occupation      = {{hlist|Actor|writer}}\n|years_active    = 2014\u2013present\n|relatives       = [[Daisy May Cooper]] (sister)<br>[[Trevor Cooper]] (uncle)\n}}\n'''Charlie Cooper''' (born 16 June 1989)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/11254372/officers|title=CHARLIE COOPER LIMITED}}</ref> is an actor and writer, known for his role as Lee \"Kurtan\" Mucklowe in the [[BBC Three]] series ''[[This Country]]'', which he co-created and co-wrote alongside his sister, [[Daisy May Cooper]].\n\n==Career==\nHe is an actor and co-writer of the [[BBC]] comedy ''[[This Country]]'' with his sister [[Daisy May Cooper]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2018-04-10/how-are-the-cast-of-this-country-related/|title=How are the cast of This Country related?|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=10 April 2018|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inews.co.uk/essentials/countrys-daisy-may-charlie-cooper-basically-experience-growing-cotswolds/amp/|title=This Country's Daisy May and Charlie Cooper: 'It's basically our experience of growing up in the Cotswolds' \u2013 iNews|website=www.inews.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/feb/22/this-country-bbc-perfect-horrifying-tv-for-anyone-who-grew-up-in-a-village|title=This Country: perfect, horrifying TV for anyone who grew up in a village|first=Stuart|last=Heritage|date=22 February 2017|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, he was nominated for and won three Royal Television Awards for best Scripted Comedy, Comedy Performance and Comedy Writing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43484081|title=This Country wins big at RTS awards|first=Neil|last=Smith|date=21 March 2018|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk|work=BBC News}}</ref> He was also nominated for and won best Scripted Comedy at the 2018 [[BAFTA]] awards for his work on ''This Country'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gloucestershirelive.co.uk/news/cheltenham-news/bafta-tv-awards-2018-how-1563408|title=How the siblings behind BBC hit This Country stole the BAFTA show|first=Ellis|last=Lane|date=14 May 2018|website=gloucestershirelive.co.uk|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref> as well as winning Breakthrough Talent at the BAFTA Craft Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/media-centre/press-releases/nominations-announced-for-tv-awards-2018|title=Nominations Announced for the Virgin TV British Academy Television Awards in 2018|website=www.bafta.org|date=2018-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/media-centre/press-releases/tv-craft-nominations-2018|title=Nominations Announced for the British Academy Television Craft Awards in 2018|website=www.bafta.org|date=2018-03-22}}</ref>\n\n \n==Personal Life==\nBrought up in [[Cirencester]], he and his sister used to make films using their mother's camcorder. He dropped out of [[Exeter University]] to live with his sister in London who was at [[RADA]] and they began writing. They both returned to their childhood home and worked night shifts as cleaners whilst creating scripts for ''This Country''. He is a fan of [[Fulham FC]], attending their play-off final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2018/may/24/charlie-cooper-exclusive |title=Charlie Cooper Exclusive |website=fulhamfc.com |date=24 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/supporting-talent/breakthrough-brits/daisy-charlie-cooper-writerperformers|title=Daisy & Charlie Cooper \u2013 Writer/Performers|website=www.bafta.org|accessdate=14 May 2018|date=2017-10-18}}</ref> Charlie Cooper confirmed that he worked at [[Argos]] in his early 20s on his Instagram account.   <ref>https://www.instagram.com/p/B_HyFX0AlDI/?hl=en</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|id=7350296}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cooper, Charlie}}\n[[Category:English television writers]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English comedians]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Gloucestershire]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n\n\n{{England-tv-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Certes", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life:Fix links to retailers, replaced:Argos\u2192Argos", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charlie_Cooper_(actor)"}
{"title_page": "Maria Espinosa", "text_new": "{{short description|American novelist, poet, and translator|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n'''Maria Espinosa''' (b. Paula Cronbach, 1939) is an [[United States|American]] [[novelist]], [[poet]], and [[translator]]. <ref>http://gentlyread.wordpress.com/2009/07/01/ample-substance-maria-espinosa-on-pamela-uschuks-crazy-love/</ref><ref>http://www.moesbooks.com/cgi-bin/moe/090506.html{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Personal Life==\nEspinosa was born January 6, 1939 in Boston Massachusetts to sculptor [[Robert Cronbach]] and a poet mother, Maxine Cronbach. She grew up on Long Island with two younger brothers, Michael Cronbach, and Lee Cronbach, a musician.  She attended Harvard and Columbia Universities and received an M.A. in Creative Writing from San Francisco State University. While living in Paris, she met and married Mario Espinosa Wellmann, a writer and photographer. Their marriage was tumultuous and lasted only a few years. In 1978 she married Walter Selig, a research chemist who fled from Nazi Germany as a child. Most of her adult life she has lived in Northern California. She currently lives in Albuquerque, New Mexico. She has one daughter from her first marriage, Carmen Espinosa, a dancer and social worker. \n\n==Career==\nAt Harvard Espinosa studied with postmodern American novelist [[John Hawkes (novelist)|John Hawkes]].  While at Columbia she sent several poems and sketches for critique to [[Anais Nin]], who was then a relatively unknown author. Nin responded favorably on pale blue airline stationary and encouraged Espinosa to write. In the 1970's and 1980's she studied at Berkeley in the private workshops of [[Leonard Bishop]], a strong literary impact on her work. She has taught at [[New College of California]], [[City College of San Francisco]], the [[University of Adelaide]], Australia, and [[Central New Mexico Community College]]. She has also led many informal writing workshops. Her poetry, articles, translations, and short fiction have appeared in numerous anthologies and periodicals. Her latest novel, ''Suburban Souls'', is forthcoming in 2020 with Tailwinds Press. (www.tailwindspress.com) \n\n==Awards==\n* 1996 [[American Book Award]] for ''Longing.''\n* 2010 [[PEN Oakland awards]] Josephine Miles Award for Literary Excellence.\n\n==Works==\n\n===Poetry===\n* ''Love Feelings'', Four Winds, 1967\n* ''Night Music'', The Tides, 1969\n\n===Novels===\n* {{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/?id=ADSC0hAzz6EC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Maria+Espinosa&cd=1#v=onepage&q=Maria%20Espinosa&f=false| title=Longing| publisher=Cayuse Press| year= 1986| isbn= 978-0-933529-01-4 }}  (reprint Arte Publico Press, 1995, {{ISBN|978-1-55885-145-0}})\n* {{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/?id=AIH2QFABrHEC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Maria+Espinosa&cd=2#v=onepage&q=Maria%20Espinosa&f=false| title=Dark Plums| publisher=Arte Publico Press| year= 1995| isbn= 978-1-55885-128-3 }}\n* {{cite book| title=Incognito: Journey of a Secret Jew| publisher=Wings Press| year= 2002| isbn= 978-0-930324-79-7 }}\n* {{cite book| title=Dying Unfinished| publisher=Wings Press| year=2009| isbn=978-0-916727-45-1| url=https://archive.org/details/dyingunfinishedn00espi}}\n*{{cite book|last=|first=|title=Suburban Souls|publisher=Tailwinds Press|year=2020|isbn=|location=|pages=|}}\n\n===Translation===\n* {{cite book| author=George Sand| title=L\u00e9lia| publisher=Indiana University Press| year= 1982| isbn= 978-0-253-20246-8 }}\n\n===Anthologies===\n*{{cite book| title=In other words: literature by Latinas of the United States| editor=Roberta Fern\u00e1ndez| publisher=Arte P\u00fablico Press| year=1994| isbn=978-1-55885-110-8| url=https://archive.org/details/inotherwordslite00fern}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.mariaespinosa.com/ \"Author's website\"]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090830102859/http://www.redroom.com/author/maria-espinosa \"Maria Espinosa\", ''Red Room'']\n*[http://gentlyread.wordpress.com/2009/07/01/ample-substance-maria-espinosa-on-pamela-uschuks-crazy-love/ \"Ample Substance: Maria Espinosa on Pamela Uschuk\u2019s ''Crazy Love''\", ''Gently Read Literature'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Espinosa, Maria}}\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:San Francisco State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:American women poets]]\n[[Category:American translators]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century American poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century translators]]\n[[Category:21st-century translators]]\n[[Category:American Book Award winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American novelist, poet, and translator|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n'''Maria Espinosa''' (b. Paula Cronbach, 1939) is an [[United States|American]] [[novelist]], [[poet]], and [[translator]]. <ref>http://gentlyread.wordpress.com/2009/07/01/ample-substance-maria-espinosa-on-pamela-uschuks-crazy-love/</ref><ref>http://www.moesbooks.com/cgi-bin/moe/090506.html{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Personal Life==\nEspinosa was born January 6, 1939 in Boston Massachusetts to sculptor [[Robert Cronbach]] and poet Maxine Judd Silver. She grew up on Long Island, NY, the oldest of three children. She attended Harvard and Columbia Universities and received an M.A. in Creative Writing from San Francisco State University. She lived in Paris where she met and married the Chilean writer and photographer Mario Espinosa Wellmann in 1966 (died 1981). In 1978 she married research chemist Walter Selig, a Holocaust survivor. His Orthodox Jewish upbringing and who he was became a major influence in Espinosa's writing. She spent the majority of her adult life in northern California. She currently lives in Albuquerque, New Mexico. She has one daughter from her first marriage, Carmen Espinosa, a dancer and social worker. \n\n==Career==\nAt Harvard Espinosa studied with postmodern American novelist [[John Hawkes (novelist)|John Hawkes]].  While at Columbia she sent several poems and sketches for critique to [[Anais Nin]], who was then a relatively unknown author. Nin responded favorably on pale blue airline stationary and encouraged Espinosa to write. In the 1970's and 1980's she studied at Berkeley in the private workshops of [[Leonard Bishop]], a strong literary impact on her work. She has taught at [[New College of California]], [[City College of San Francisco]], the [[University of Adelaide]], Australia, and [[Central New Mexico Community College]]. She has also led many informal writing workshops. Her poetry, articles, translations, and short fiction have appeared in numerous anthologies and periodicals. Her latest novel, ''Suburban Souls'', is forthcoming in 2020 with Tailwinds Press. (www.tailwindspress.com) \n\n==Awards==\n* 1996 [[American Book Award]] for ''Longing.''\n* 2010 [[PEN Oakland awards]] Josephine Miles Award for Literary Excellence.\n\n==Works==\n\n===Poetry===\n* ''Love Feelings'', Four Winds, 1967\n* ''Night Music'', The Tides, 1969\n\n===Novels===\n* {{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/?id=ADSC0hAzz6EC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Maria+Espinosa&cd=1#v=onepage&q=Maria%20Espinosa&f=false| title=Longing| publisher=Cayuse Press| year= 1986| isbn= 978-0-933529-01-4 }}  (reprint Arte Publico Press, 1995, {{ISBN|978-1-55885-145-0}})\n* {{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/?id=AIH2QFABrHEC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Maria+Espinosa&cd=2#v=onepage&q=Maria%20Espinosa&f=false| title=Dark Plums| publisher=Arte Publico Press| year= 1995| isbn= 978-1-55885-128-3 }}\n* {{cite book| title=Incognito: Journey of a Secret Jew| publisher=Wings Press| year= 2002| isbn= 978-0-930324-79-7 }}\n* {{cite book| title=Dying Unfinished| publisher=Wings Press| year=2009| isbn=978-0-916727-45-1| url=https://archive.org/details/dyingunfinishedn00espi}}\n*{{cite book|last=|first=|title=Suburban Souls|publisher=Tailwinds Press|year=2020|isbn=|location=|pages=|}}\n\n===Translation===\n* {{cite book| author=George Sand| title=L\u00e9lia| publisher=Indiana University Press| year= 1982| isbn= 978-0-253-20246-8 }}\n\n===Anthologies===\n*{{cite book| title=In other words: literature by Latinas of the United States| editor=Roberta Fern\u00e1ndez| publisher=Arte P\u00fablico Press| year=1994| isbn=978-1-55885-110-8| url=https://archive.org/details/inotherwordslite00fern}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.mariaespinosa.com/ \"Author's website\"]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090830102859/http://www.redroom.com/author/maria-espinosa \"Maria Espinosa\", ''Red Room'']\n*[http://gentlyread.wordpress.com/2009/07/01/ample-substance-maria-espinosa-on-pamela-uschuks-crazy-love/ \"Ample Substance: Maria Espinosa on Pamela Uschuk\u2019s ''Crazy Love''\", ''Gently Read Literature'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Espinosa, Maria}}\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:San Francisco State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:American women poets]]\n[[Category:American translators]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century American poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century translators]]\n[[Category:21st-century translators]]\n[[Category:American Book 