/coronavirus-european-borders-likely-remain-open-despite-crisis |archive-date=15 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> the [[European Union]] by 13 March continued to reject the idea of suspending the [[Schengen Area|Schengen free travel area]] and introducing border controls with Italy.<ref name=\"dw-schengen\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.dw.com/en/coronavirus-eu-rules-out-schengen-border-closures-amid-italy-outbreak/a-52497811 |title=Coronavirus: EU rules out Schengen border closures amid Italy outbreak |date=24 February 2020 |publisher=Deutsche Welle |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313142436/https://www.dw.com/en/coronavirus-eu-rules-out-schengen-border-closures-amid-italy-outbreak/a-52497811 |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2020-02-25/salvini-and-le-pen-don-t-have-a-european-coronavirus-cure |title=Salvini and Le Pen Don't Have a Coronavirus Cure |date=25 February 2020 |work=Bloomberg |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227122244/https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2020-02-25/salvini-and-le-pen-don-t-have-a-european-coronavirus-cure |archive-date=27 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/coronavirus-europe-open-borders-eu-italy-france-britain-germany-spain-a9362536.html |title=Coronavirus: Europe's open borders threatened by spread of disease |date=28 February 2020 |work=The Independent |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317173409/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/coronavirus-europe-open-borders-eu-italy-france-britain-germany-spain-a9362536.html |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/justice-home-affairs/news/commission-chief-warns-against-unilateral-virus-travel-bans/ |title=Commission chief warns against unilateral virus travel bans |date=13 March 2020 |work=[[EURACTIV]] |access-date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318195056/https://www.euractiv.com/section/justice-home-affairs/news/commission-chief-warns-against-unilateral-virus-travel-bans/ |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The deputy leader of the Swiss [[Ticino League]], Lorenzo Quadri, by 29 February had criticised the decision: \"It is alarming that the dogma of wide-open borders is considered a priority.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/26/world/europe/coronavirus-european-union.html |title=Coronavirus Nightmare Could Be the End for Europe's Borderless Dream |date=26 February 2020 |work=The New York Times |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303055756/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/26/world/europe/coronavirus-european-union.html |archive-date=3 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> United States President [[Donald Trump]] said by 12 March the European Union had \"failed to take the same precautions and restrict travel from China and other hot spots\" as the US had implemented.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-trump/trump-suspends-all-travel-from-europe-to-the-united-states-to-fight-coronavirus-idUSKBN20Z04U |title=In dramatic step, Trump restricts travel from Europe to US to fight coronavirus |date=12 March 2020 |agency=Reuters |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314140433/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-trump/trump-suspends-all-travel-from-europe-to-the-united-states-to-fight-coronavirus-idUSKBN20Z04U |archive-date=14 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Trump also said that \"As a result a large number of new clusters in the United States were seeded by travellers from Europe.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: What you need to know about Trump's Europe travel ban |url=https://www.thelocal.dk/20200312/trump-imposes-travel-ban-from-europe-over-coronavirus-outbreak |work=The Local |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> Research on [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|coronavirus genomes]] indicates the majority of COVID-19 cases in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)|New York]] came from European travelers, rather than directly from China or any other Asian country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Studies Show N.Y. Outbreak Originated in Europe|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/08/us/coronavirus-live-updates.html |work=The New York Times |date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> \n\nBy 9 March Czech Prime Minister [[Andrej Babi\u0161]] stated that \"European countries cannot ban the entry of Italian citizens within the Schengen area. The only possible way is to have the Italian prime minister call on his fellow citizens to refrain from traveling to other countries of the European Union.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.schengenvisainfo.com/news/czech-pm-italians-should-be-banned-from-travelling-due-to-coronavirus/ |title=Czech PM: Italians Should Be Banned From Travelling Due to Coronavirus |date=9 March 2020 |work=SchengenVisaInfo.com |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323171345/https://www.schengenvisainfo.com/news/czech-pm-italians-should-be-banned-from-travelling-due-to-coronavirus/ |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAfter Czech Republic, Slovakia, Poland and Denmark announced complete closure of their national borders, the [[European Commission]] President [[Ursula von der Leyen]] said by 12 March that \"Certain controls may be justified, but general travel bans are not seen as being the most effective by the World Health Organization. Moreover, they have a strong social and economic impact, they disrupt people\u2019s lives and business across the borders.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/4e89ec5c-6565-11ea-b3f3-fe4680ea68b5 |title=Denmark, Poland and Czechs seal borders over coronavirus |date=12 March 2020 |agency=Financial Times |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314202823/https://www.ft.com/content/4e89ec5c-6565-11ea-b3f3-fe4680ea68b5 |archive-date=14 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> European Union leaders condemned the US decision to restrict travel from Europe to the United States. [[European Council]] President [[Charles Michel]] and Ursula von der Leyen said in a joint statement: \"The European Union disapproves of the fact that the US decision to impose a travel ban was taken unilaterally and without consultation.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://apnews.com/4552fd280d06cf83c63e4cc9b08fe5ce |title=EU condemns Trump travel ban from Europe as virus spreads |date=12 March 2020 |work=Associated Press (AP) |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313140528/https://apnews.com/4552fd280d06cf83c63e4cc9b08fe5ce |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Ursula von der Leyen admitted by 17 March that \"all of us who are not experts initially underestimated the coronavirus.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/coronavirus/news/politicians-underestimated-virus-threat-von-der-leyen-admits/ |title=Politicians 'underestimated' virus threat, von der Leyen admits |date=18 March 2020 |work=Euractiv |access-date=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319152350/https://www.euractiv.com/section/coronavirus/news/politicians-underestimated-virus-threat-von-der-leyen-admits/ |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe Italian government has criticised EU's lack of solidarity with Italy.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/03/14/coronavirus-eu-abandoning-italy-china-aid/ |title=The EU Is Abandoning Italy in Its Hour of Need |date=14 March 2020 |work=Foreign Policy |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315112947/https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/03/14/coronavirus-eu-abandoning-italy-china-aid/ |archive-date=15 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/11/italy-criticises-eu-being-slow-help-coronavirus-epidemic |title=Italy criticises EU for being slow to help over coronavirus epidemic |date=11 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313000621/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/11/italy-criticises-eu-being-slow-help-coronavirus-epidemic |archive-date=13 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/d3bc25ea-652c-11ea-b3f3-fe4680ea68b5 |title=Italy wonders where Europe's solidarity is as coronavirus strains show |date=13 March 2020 |work=Financial Times |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315154437/https://www.ft.com/content/d3bc25ea-652c-11ea-b3f3-fe4680ea68b5 |archive-date=15 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.cgtn.com/news/2020-03-12/Italy-calls-for-extra-help-for-COVID-19-only-China-responded--ONp6w2rmvu/index.html |title=Italy criticizes EU for not responding its call for help, 'only China responded bilaterally' |date=12 March 2020 |work=CGTN |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316024124/https://news.cgtn.com/news/2020-03-12/Italy-calls-for-extra-help-for-COVID-19-only-China-responded--ONp6w2rmvu/index.html |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Politico'' reported on 7 March that \"EU countries have so far refused Italy's plea for help fighting coronavirus, as national capitals worry that they may need to stockpile face masks and other medical gear to help their own citizens, officials and diplomats said.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/eu-aims-better-control-coronavirus-responses/ |title=Europe fails to help Italy in coronavirus fight |date=7 March 2020 |work=Politico |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317055659/https://www.politico.eu/article/eu-aims-better-control-coronavirus-responses/ |archive-date=17 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Maurizio Massari, Italy's ambassador to the EU, said that \"Only China responded bilaterally. Certainly, this is not a good sign of European solidarity.\"<ref name=\"politico-corona\" /> [[Serbia]]n President [[Aleksandar Vu\u010di\u0107]] said that \"European solidarity does not exist. That was a fairy tale.\"<ref name=\"politico-corona\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.politico.eu/article/coronavirus-china-winning-propaganda-war/ |title=China is winning the coronavirus propaganda war |date=18 March 2020 |work=Politico |access-date=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322203919/https://www.politico.eu/article/coronavirus-china-winning-propaganda-war/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n[[File:Reivindicaciones 8M (49637966373).jpg|thumb|[[International Women's Day]] march in M\u00e9rida, Spain, 8 March<ref>{{cite news |title=Thousands March in Spain on Women's Day Despite Coronavirus Fears |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2020-03-08/thousands-march-in-spain-on-womens-day-despite-coronavirus-fears |date=8 March 2020 |work=[[US News]] |agency=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>]]\nAccording to ''The Guardian'', [[Spain]]'s initially slow response to the coronavirus caused the epidemic to become severe even though it did not share a land border with Italy or other severely affected countries.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tremlett |first1=Giles |title=How did Spain get its coronavirus response so wrong? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/26/spain-coronavirus-response-analysis |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=26 March 2020}}</ref> An analysis in ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'' hypothesised that the minority government did not want to risk its hold on power by banning large gatherings early; Prime Minister [[Pedro S\u00e1nchez]] initially defended his decision to allow large gatherings to continue.<ref name=Vox>{{cite news |last1=Ward |first1=Alex |title=How Spain's coronavirus outbreak got so bad so fast |url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/20/21183315/coronavirus-spain-outbreak-cases-tests |work=Vox |date=20 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe planned [[NATO]] \u201c[[List of NATO exercises|Defender 2020]]\u201d military exercise in Germany, Poland, and the Baltic states,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/how-coronavirus-derailed-the-largest-nato-exercise-in-25-years |title=How coronavirus derailed the largest Nato exercise in 25 years |date=20 March 2020 |work=The Spectator |access-date=25 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325102257/https://www.spectator.co.uk/article/how-coronavirus-derailed-the-largest-nato-exercise-in-25-years |archive-date=25 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> the largest NATO war manoeuvres since the end of the [[Cold War]], was to be held on a reduced scale because of the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-nato/nato-scales-down-exercises-due-to-coronavirus-idUSKBN21627V |title=NATO scales down exercises due to coronavirus |date=19 March 2020 |agency=Reuters |access-date=25 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325102254/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-nato/nato-scales-down-exercises-due-to-coronavirus-idUSKBN21627V |archive-date=25 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament]]'s general secretary [[Kate Hudson (activist)|Kate Hudson]] critisiced the Defender 2020 exercise: \"In the current public-health crisis, it jeopardises the lives not only of the troops from the US and the many European countries participating but the inhabitants of the countries in which they are operating.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/b/nato-must-end-dangerous-and-irresponsible-military-exercise-on-russias-border-campaigners-say |title=Nato must end 'dangerous and irresponsible' military exercise on Russia's border, campaigners say |date=18 March 2020 |work=Morning Star |access-date=25 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320010441/https://morningstaronline.co.uk/article/b/nato-must-end-dangerous-and-irresponsible-military-exercise-on-russias-border-campaigners-say |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"OKOpress_Szumowski_EU_claims\">{{cite news | last1= Pa\u0144kowska | first1= Maria | language =pl | title= Szumowski krytykuje UE: 'Nie ma tej europejskiej solidarno\u015bci'. To wielopi\u0119trowy fa\u0142sz |trans-title = Szumowski criticise the EU: 'There is no European solidarity'. Which is false at many levels<!-- trans-title is the English translation --> | date= 2020-03-26 |newspaper= [[OKO.press]] | url= https://oko.press/szumowski-krytykuje-ue-nie-ma-tej-europejskiej-solidarnosci-to-wielopietrowy-falsz/ |quote= Bo jak by\u015bmy czekali na inne kraje, na Europ\u0119, na \u015bwiat, to by\u015bmy si\u0119 obudzili bez \u015brodk\u00f3w, a dooko\u0142a wszyscy by te \u015brodki sobie zakupili ... \u017beby by\u0142a jasno\u015b\u0107, to nie jest tak, \u017ce my ten sprz\u0119t mamy w Europie, \u017ce s\u0105 jego nieograniczone ilo\u015bci. ... Bo niestety tutaj centralne zakupy zawiod\u0142y, nie ma tej europejskiej solidarno\u015bci.  |accessdate=2020-03-26 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200326225848/https://oko.press/szumowski-krytykuje-ue-nie-ma-tej-europejskiej-solidarnosci-to-wielopietrowy-falsz/ |archivedate= 2020-03-26 |url-status=live <!-- live|dead|unfit|usurped --> |url-access = <!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free -->}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://corona.arrangy.com Worldwide Coronavirus Map, confirmed Cases] \u2013 Map the route paths of coronavirus confirmed cases.\n* [https://systems.jhu.edu/research/public-health/ncov/ ncov \u2013 CSSE] \u2013 Map of the expansion of the virus in Europe and in the world\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe| ]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by continent|Europe]]\n[[Category:2020 disasters in Europe|coronavirus outbreak]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in Europe]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Ondoro", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStatistics by country and territory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Europe"}
{"title_page": "Economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in India", "text_new": "{{short description|Impact of COVID-19 in the economy of India}}\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in India|Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\nThe '''economic impact of the 2019\u201320 COVID-19\n pandemic in India''' has been hugely disruptive. [[World Bank]] and [[Credit rating agency|credit rating agencies]] have downgraded India's growth for [[fiscal year]] 2021 with the lowest figures India has seen in three decades since India's [[Economic liberalisation in India|economic liberalization in the 1990s]].<ref name=\":25\" /><ref name=\":26\" /> However, the [[International Monetary Fund]] projection for India for the [[Financial Year|financial year]] 2021-22 of 1.9% GDP growth is the highest among [[G20|G-20]] nations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/business/story/rbi-governor-shaktikanta-das-indian-economy-covid19-imf-projection-gdp-growth-1667889-2020-04-17|title=IMF projection for India\u2019s GDP growth highest in G-20, says RBI Governor Shaktikanta Das|last=|first=|date=17 April 2020|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Indian economy]] is expected to lose over {{INRConvert|32000|c|lk=on|year=2020}} every day during the first [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|21-days of complete lockdown]] which was declared following the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India|coronavirus outbreak]].<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/covid-19-lockdown-estimated-to-cost-india-45-billion-a-day-acuit-ratings/article31235264.ece|title=Covid-19 lockdown estimated to cost India $4.5 billion a day: Acuit\u00e9 Ratings|last=|first=|date=2 April 2020|website=The Hindu Business Line|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref name=\":24\" /> Under complete lockdown less than a quarter of India's $2.8 trillion economy is functional.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/policy/economy/news/lockdown-relaxation-more-than-half-of-indian-economy-may-reopen-from-monday-april-20/articleshow/75220299.cms|title=Lockdown relaxation\u2060\u2014 more than half of India's economy may reopen from Monday, says Nomura|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> Up to 53% of businesses in the country will be significantly affected.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/companies/news/coronavirus-impact-indian-industry-seeks-relief-measures-to-aid-economy-11584904435575.html|title=Coronavirus impact: Indian industry seeks relief measures to aid economy|last=Biman.Mukherji|date=2020-03-23|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> [[Supply chain]]s have been put under stress with the lockdown restrictions in place; initially there was a lack of clarity in streamlining what is an \"essential\" and what isn't.<ref name=\"Chaudhry\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/agri-business/covid-19-puts-indias-food-supply-chain-to-a-stress-test/article31173973.ece|title=Covid-19 puts India's food supply chain to a stress-test|last=Chaudhry|first=Siraj A.|date=26 March 2020|website=The Hindu @businessline|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Those in the informal sectors and daily wage groups are the most at risk.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/136-million-jobs-at-risk-in-post-corona-india-11585584169192.html|title=136 million jobs at risk in post-corona India|last=Das|first=Goutam|date=2020-03-30|website=Livemint|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> A large number of farmers around the country who grow [[Perishable food|perishables]] are also facing uncertainty.<ref name=\"Chaudhry\" /> Various businesses such as hotels and airlines are cutting salaries and laying off employees.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Goyal|first=Malini|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/finance/covid-19-crisis-how-the-deadly-virus-hints-at-a-looming-financial-crisis/articleshow/74752200.cms|title=Covid-19: How the deadly virus hints at a looming financial crisis|date=2020-03-22|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The live events industry has seen an estimated loss of {{INRConvert|3000|c|lk=on|year=2020}}.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nMajor companies in India such as [[Larsen & Toubro|Larsen and Toubro]], [[Bharat Forge]], [[UltraTech Cement]], [[Grasim Industries]], [[Aditya Birla Group]], [[Tata Motors]] and [[Thermax]] have temporarily suspended or significantly reduced operations. [[iPhone]] producing companies in India have also suspended a majority of operations. Young startups have been impacted as [[Venture capital financing|funding]] has fallen.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/young-indian-startups-hit-as-investors-get-cautious/1787866|title=Young Indian startups hit as investors get cautious|date=1 April 2020|website=Outlook India|others=IANS|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://inc42.com/datalab/pandemic-impacts-funding-prospects-for-startups-after-slow-q1-2020|title=Covid-19 Pandemic Spoils Indian Startup Funding Party, Growth Stage Worst Hit In Q1 2020|last=Singh|first=Sandeep|date=2020-04-01|website=Inc42 Media|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In the third week of March, [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] and [[Walmart]]-owned [[Flipkart]] announced that it would stop sale of non-essential items in India so that it could focus on essential deliveries.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/amazon-to-stop-non-essential-sales-in-india-2200154|title=Amazon To Stop Non-Essential Sales In India|date=24 March 2020|website=NDTV|others=Reuters|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Other fast-moving consumer goods companies in the country have significantly reduced operations and are focusing on essentials. Stock markets in [[India]] posted their worst loses in history on 23 March 2020.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/business/market/bse-sensex-nse-nifty-stock-market-live-updates-coronavirus-global-markets-6327415/|title=Stock markets post worst losses in history; Sensex crashes 3,935 points amid coronavirus lockdown|date=2020-03-23|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> However, on 25 March, one day after a complete [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|21 day lockdown]] was announced by the Prime Minister, [[SENSEX]] and [[NIFTY 50|NIFTY]] posted their biggest gains in 11 years, adding a value of  {{INRConvert|4.7|lc|lk=on|year=2020}} crore to investor wealth.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|last=Shah|first=Ami|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/sensex-logs-biggest-one-day-gain-in-11-years-investors-richer-by-rs-4-7-lakh-crore/articleshow/74810933.cms|title=Sensex posts biggest gain in 11 years: Investors richer by Rs 4.7 lakh crore|date=2020-03-25|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n{{Quote box\n| quote = \"From the economy's point of view, the lockdown undoubtedly looks costly right now, but compared to the lives of Indian citizens, it is nothing.\" ''(translation, original in Hindi)''\n| author = Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]], speech to the nation, 10 am, 14 April 2020.\n| source = <ref>{{cite news |title=Economic cost of lockdown is nothing compared to people's lives: PM Modi |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/economic-cost-of-lockdown-is-nothing-compared-to-people-s-lives-pm-modi-120041400359_1.html |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=Business Standard |agency=ANI |date=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Lockdown hurts economy but saving life is more important: PM Modi |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/lockdown-hurts-economy-but-saving-lives-is-more-important-pm-modi-1666725-2020-04-14 |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=India Today |date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n| width = 300px\n| fontsize = 110%\n}}\nThe [[Government of India]] has announced a variety of measures to tackle the situation, from [[food security]] and extra funds for healthcare, to sector related incentives and tax deadline extensions. On 27 March the [[Reserve Bank of India]] also announced a number of measures which would make available {{INRConvert|374000|c|lk=on|year=2020}} to the country's financial system. On 29 March the government allowed the movement of all essential as well as non-essential goods during the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown]].<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/covid-19-govt-allows-transportation-of-all-essential-non-essential-goods-120033000055_1.html|title=Covid-19: Govt allows transportation of all essential, non-essential goods|date=2020-03-30|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-03-30|url-status=live|agency=PTI}}</ref> On 1 April, [[World Bank]] approved $1 bn in support to India to tackle the coronavirus pandemic. On 3 April the central government released more funds to the states for tackling the coronavirus totalling to {{INRConvert|28379|c|lk=on|year=2020}}. On 6 April a 30% salary cut for one year was announced for the President, Prime Minister and Members of Parliament.<ref name=\":21\" />\n\nOn 14 April 2020, the Prime Minister of India extended the lockdown to 3 May. A new set of guidelines for the calibrated opening of the economy and relaxation of the lockdown were also set in place which will take effect from 20 April.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sharma|first=Aman|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/india-evolves-worlds-largest-smart-model-0f-lockdown-officials/articleshow/75169336.cms|title=India evolves world\u2019s largest smart model of lockdown: Officials|date=2020-04-16|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> On 17 April, the [[RBI Governor]] announced more measures to counter the economic impact of the pandemic including {{INRConvert|50000|c|lk=on|year=2020}} special finance to [[National Bank for Agriculture and Rural Development|NABARD]], [[Small Industries Development Bank of India|SIDBI]], and [[National Housing Bank|NHB]].<ref name=\":30\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/economy/rbi-governor-shaktikanta-das-live-news-updates-fiscal-stimulus-monetary-policy-economic-relief-coronavirus/1931155/|title=RBI Governor Highlights: Shaktikanta Das cuts reverse repo; pumps in money, liquidity; eases rules for banks, NBFCs|date=2020-04-17|website=The Financial Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March the [[Press Information Bureau]] brought out a fact check that stories about a financial emergency being imposed in India are fake.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/stop-panicking-pm-modi-is-not-declaring-an-emergency-stay-away-from-fake-news/articleshow/74791920.cms|title=Stop Panicking: PM Modi is not declaring an emergency; Stay Away from Fake News|last=|first=|date=24 March 2020|website=Mumbai Mirror|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> A [[Financial Emergency in India|financial emergency]] has never been imposed in the history of India as yet.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2020/03/21/is-declaration-of-economic-emergency-inevitable-asks-subramanian-swamy.html|title=Is declaration of economic emergency inevitable, asks Subramanian Swamy|last=|first=|date=21 March 2020|website=The Week|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> On 4 April, former RBI chief [[Raghuram Rajan]] said that the coronavirus pandemic in India may just be the \"greatest emergency since Independence\".<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/greatest-emergency-since-independence-rbi-chief-raghuram-rajan-on-covid-19-2206716|title=\"Greatest Emergency Since Independence\": Raghuram Rajan On COVID-19|last=Ghosh|first=Deepshikha|date=6 April 2020|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n== Lives versus livelihood debate ==\n\n=== 24 March: ''Jaan hai toh jahaan hai'' (only if there is life there will be livelihood)  ===\nPrime Minister Modi announced the first 21 days of India's lockdown on 24 March. During this address to the nation he had said, \"''Jaan Hai Toh Jahaan Hai'' (only if there is life there will be livelihood)\".<ref name=\":29\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/modi-says-jaan-bhi-jahaan-bhi-signals-a-shift-in-india-s-coronavirus-playbook-11586606578037.html|title=Modi says \u2018jaan bhi jahaan bhi', signals a shift in India\u2019s coronavirus playbook|last=Khanna|first=Utpal Bhaskar,Anuja,Pretika|date=2020-04-11|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/opinion/columns/new-delhi-revisits-the-lives-versus-livelihood-debate-11586710892651.html|title=Opinion {{!}} New Delhi revisits the lives versus livelihood debate|last=Padmanabhan|first=Anil|date=2020-04-12|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n=== 11 April: ''Jaan bhi jahaan bhi'' (both lives and livelihood matter equally)  ===\nOn 11 April, in a meeting with the Chief Ministers of India, he said \"Our mantra earlier was ''jaan hai toh jahaan hai'' but now it is ''jaan bhi jahaan bhi'' (both, lives and livelihood matter equally).\"<ref name=\":29\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/pm-modi-s-meeting-with-chief-ministers-five-things-to-watch-out-for-11586576286173.html|title=PM Modi's meeting with chief ministers: Five things to watch out for|last=Varma,Anuja|first=Gyan|date=2020-04-11|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> On 14 April, another address to the nation was made by Modi in which he extended the lockdown, with adjustments, to 3 May.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/opinion/indias-lockdown-2-can-cost-as-many-lives-as-it-saves/402269/|title=No matter how you look at it, India\u2019s lockdown-2 can cost as many lives as it will save|last=Yadav|first=Yogendra|date=2020-04-15|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== Government actions ==\n\n=== Timeline ===\n\n* On '''21 March 2020''', the [[Union cabinet|Union Cabinet]] approved incentives worth {{INRConvert|40995|c|lk=on|year=2020}} for electronic manufacturing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/business/cabinet-approves-production-linked-incentives-for-electronics-manufacturing-firms-2|title=Cabinet Approves Production-Linked Incentives For Electronics Manufacturing Firms|date=|website=BloombergQuint|language=en|others=PTI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Phartiyal|first=Sankalp|url=https://in.reuters.com/article/india-electronics-idINKBN2190JJ|title=India lays out $6 billion roadmap to boost electronics manufacturing|date=2020-03-22|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-23|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref>\n*Various state governments have announced financial assistance for the poor in the unorganised sector. On '''21 March''' the [[Government of Uttar Pradesh|Uttar Pradesh government]] decided to give a direct money transfer of {{INRConvert|1000||lk=|year=2020}} to all daily wage laborers in the state<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/yogi-adityanath-announces-relief-measures-for-ups-daily-wage-earners/articleshow/74744711.cms|title=Yogi Adityanath announces relief measures for UP's daily wage earners|author=|website=Economic times}}</ref> and the following day [[Punjab]] announced {{INRConvert|3000||lk=|year=2020}} each for all registered construction workers in state.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chandigarh/coronavirus-rs-3000-relief-for-construction-workers-says-punjab-cm-amarinder-singh/articleshow/74754595.cms|title=Coronavirus: Rs 3,000 relief for construction workers, says Punjab CM Amarinder Singh|date=22 March 2020|work=The Times of India|accessdate=22 March 2020|agency=TNN}}</ref> On '''23 March''' it was announced that Haryana labourers, street vendors and rickshaw pullers will be provided an assistance of \u20b91,000 per week directly deposited into their bank accounts. [[Below Poverty Line]] families will be provided rations (including rice, wheat, mustard oil, sugar) free of cost for the month of April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/chandigarh/all-15-haryana-dists-locked-down-financial-support-announced-for-the-poor/story-yguH21C7I59Sj7G8oIweJL.html|title=All 15 Haryana dists locked down, financial support announced for the poor|date=2020-03-23|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n* On '''24 March''', in his address to the nation, the Prime Minister announced a {{INRConvert|15000|c|lk=on|year=2020}} fund for the healthcare sector.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/india/pm-declares-21-day-full-lockdown-across-india-from-midnight-rs-15000-cr-to-fight-covid-19/387457/|title=PM declares 21-day full lockdown across India from midnight, Rs 15,000 cr to fight COVID-19|last=Chandna|first=Himani|last2=Basu|first2=Mohana|date=24 March 2020|website=ThePrint|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n* On '''24 March''' at 2:30pm, the Finance Minister made a number of announcements related to the economy such as extending last dates for filing [[Goods and Services Tax (India)|GST]] returns and income tax returns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/finance-minister-nirmala-sitharaman-live-updates-coronavirus-outbreak-india-economic-package-announcement-media-briefing-news-today-8182241.html|title=FM Nirmala Sitharaman on Coronavirus Outbreak LIVE Updates: Firms with less than Rs 5 cr turnover, no interest, penalty, late fee on late GST return filing|website=Firstpost|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>  The due dates for the Sabka Vishwas (Legacy Dispute Resolution) Scheme 2019, customs clearances and for compliance matters under the Customs Act and associated laws has been extended to June 2020.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://mercomindia.com/finance-ministry-economic-relief-measures-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Finance Ministry Announces Economic Relief Measures Amid Coronavirus Outbreak|last=Parikh|first=Anjana|date=2020-03-24|website=Mercom India|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n* On '''25 March''' the [[Modi government]] announced the world's largest [[food security]] scheme for 80 crore (800,000,000 people) across the country.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/economy/modi-govts-largest-ration-subsidy-scheme-for-80-cr-indians-buy-rice-wheat-at-this-price/1909103/|title=Modi govt's largest ration subsidy scheme for 80 Cr Indians; check full details of govt plan|last=Sharma|first=Samrat|date=25 March 2020|website=The Financial Express|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Cabinet Minister [[Prakash Javadekar]] made the announcement in a press conference that the ration would be 7&nbsp;kg every month (which includes wheat at a cost of {{INRConvert|2||lk=on|year=2020}} per kg and rice at  {{INRConvert|3||lk=on|year=2020}} per kg.)<ref name=\":9\" />\n* On '''25 March''' the Uttar Pradesh government banned the manufacture and sale of [[pan masala]], stating in the order that \"Spitting pan masala can help in spreading Covid-19\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/up-govt-bans-manufacture-sale-of-pan-masala-to-fight-coronavirus-spread-11585140181755.html|title=UP govt bans manufacture, sale of pan masala to fight coronavirus spread|date=2020-03-25|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Following this, other states such as Andhra Pradesh, Rajasthan and Gujarat also banned spitting in public places.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_in/article/pkev9m/gujarat-banned-spitting-to-stop-coronavirus|title=It Took Coronavirus for an Indian State to Ban Spitting in Public|last=Solani|first=Dhvani|date=2020-03-16|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/coronavirus-groups-hail-ban-on-spitting-in-rajasthan/article31319937.ece|title=Coronavirus {{!}} Groups hail ban on spitting in Rajasthan|date=2020-04-11|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-13|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/andhra-pradesh/2020/apr/12/andhra-pradesh-government-bans-spitting-in-public-places-2129100.html|title=Andhra Pradesh government bans spitting in public places|last=|first=|date=12 April 2020|website=The New Indian Express|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n*On '''26 March''' the Finance Minister announced a number of economic relief measures for the poor. {{INRConvert|170000|c|lk=on|year=2020}} will fund the [[Pradhan Mantri Garib Kalyan Yojana]] which will provide both cash transfer and food security; with the aim that no one goes hungry amidst the lockdown.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/fm-nirmala-sitharaman-announces-rs-1-7-lakh-crore-relief-package-for-poor/articleshow/74825054.cms|title=FM Nirmala Sitharaman announces Rs 1.7 lakh crore relief package for poor|date=2020-03-26|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> [[Pradhan Mantri Ujjwala Yojana]] beneficiaries will get free cylinders for at least three months. This will benefit over 8 crore [[Below Poverty Line|below poverty line]] families.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/business/story/finance-minister-nirmala-sitharaman-live-updates-economic-relief-package-india-coronavirus-1659912-2020-03-26|title=Coronavirus: FM Sitharaman announces package worth Rs 1,70,000 crore for poor, daily wagers|last=|first=|date=26 March 2020|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>  The government will expedite payment of the first instalment (\u20b92,000) due in 2020\u201321 in April itself under the Pradhan Mantri Kisan Samman Nidhi (PM-KISAN). For the organised sector worker, the government will pay the Employees\u2019 Provident Fund (EPF) contributions of both sides for 80 lakh employees of small companies who earn up to \u20b915,000 a month.The raise in the threshold from \u20b91lakh to \u20b91crore for triggering insolvency proceedings under the Insolvency and Bankruptcy Code (IBC) will help MSMEs. State governments were given various instructions and guidelines such as diverting district mineral funds for health needs relating to the pandemic.<ref name=\":12\" />\n*On '''26 March''' India participated in the virtual 'Extraordinary G20 Leaders\u2019 Summit'. The G20 nations decided to inject over $5 trillion into the global economy to counteract the pandemic's impacts. They agreed to work together, to strengthen the World Health Organisation, develop a vaccine and make it available. They decided to share timely and transparent information, materials for research and development and data. Besides expanding manufacturing capacity for medical supplies, they agreed to ensure smooth flows of critical supplies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/business/g20-leaders-pledge-usd-5-trillion-united-response-to-coronavirus-crisis/articleshow/74835666.cms|title=G20 leaders pledge USD 5 trillion, 'united' response to coronavirus crisis|date=2020-03-26|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>[https://g20.org/en/media/Documents/G20_Extraordinary%20G20%20Leaders%E2%80%99%20Summit_Statement_EN%20(3).pdf G20 Leaders\u2019 Statement, Extraordinary G20 Leaders\u2019 Summit Statement on COVID-19]. Retrieved on 5 April 2020.</ref>\n*On '''27 March''' the [[Reserve Bank of India]] (RBI) Governor [[Shaktikanta Das]] made a number of announcements including EMIs being put on hold for three months and reducing [[Repo Rate|repo rates]]. Other measures introduced will make available a total {{INRConvert|374000|c|lk=on|year=2020}} to the country's financial system.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/rbi-joins-coronavirus-fight-rolls-out-big-bang-rate-move/articleshow/74840568.cms|title=RBI joins coronavirus fight with big-bang rate move, EMIs put on hold|date=27 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-27|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Government of Delhi|Delhi government]] announced that from the 28th they will be providing free food to 400,000 every day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/latest/trends/4-lakh-people-to-get-free-food-in-delhi-coronavirus-treatment-capacity-to-be-raised-to-1000-patients-per-day/story/399405.html|title=4 lakh people to get free food in Delhi, coronavirus treatment capacity to be raised to 1,000 patients per day|last=|first=|date=27 March 2020|website=Business Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Over 500 hunger relief centres have been set by the Delhi government.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/govt-to-give-2-meals-a-day-to-4-lakh-people-says-kejriwal/articleshow/74855058.cms|title=Delhi lockdown: Over 500 hunger relief centres set up for 4 lakh people|last=Mathur|first=Atul|date=28 March 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n*On '''28 March''' the Prime Minister launched a new fund called [[PM CARES fund]] for combating such situations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/pm-cares-pm-narendra-modi-announces-new-covid-19-fund-gets-rs-25-crore-from-akshay-kumar-2202275|title=PM Modi Announces New COVID-19 Fund, Gets Rs 25 Crore From Akshay Kumar|last=|first=|date=28 March 2020|editor-last=Roy|editor-first=Divyanshu Dutta|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n*On '''30 March''' it was announced that the UP government would transfer {{INRConvert|611|c|lk=on|year=2020}} to 27.15 lakh workers under [[National Rural Employment Guarantee Act, 2005|MNREGA]] scheme.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newsonair.com/Main-News-Details.aspx?title=Uttar-Pradesh-govt-to--transfer-Rs-611-crore-in-accounts-of-27.15-lakh-MNREGA-labourers-today&id=384172|title=Uttar Pradesh govt to transfer Rs 611 crore in accounts of 27.15 lakh MNREGA labourers today|last=|first=|date=30 March 2020|website=News on Air, All India Radio|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n*On '''1 April''' the RBI announced more measures to deal with the economic fallout of COVID-19.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|last=Nayak|first=Gayatri|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/rbi-announces-more-measures-to-deal-with-economic-fallout-of-covid-19/articleshow/74926767.cms|title=RBI announces more measures to deal with economic fallout of COVID-19|date=2020-04-01|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> [[Ways and means advances|WMA]] and short-term liquidity has been increased to provide relief to state governments; exporters have also been granted some relief in the form of relaxed repatriation limits.<ref name=\":14\" />\n*On '''2 April''' the [[World Bank]] approved $1 bn emergency financing for India to tackle coronavirus labelled 'India COVID-19 Emergency Response and Health Systems Preparedness Project'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldbank.org/en/news/press-release/2020/04/02/world-bank-fast-tracks-1-billion-covid-19-support-for-india|title=World Bank Fast-Tracks $1 Billion COVID-19 (Coronavirus) Support for India|website=World Bank|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/world-bank-approves-1-bn-emergency-financing-for-india-to-tackle-coronavirus-11585852036102.html|title=World Bank approves $1 bn emergency financing for India to tackle coronavirus|date=2020-04-03|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/indicators/covid-fight-is-a-balancing-act-for-worlds-economies-world-bank-india-chief/articleshow/74964031.cms|title=Covid fight is a balancing act for world's economies: World Bank India Chief|date=2020-04-03|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n*On '''3 April''' the central government released {{INRConvert|17287|c|lk=on|year=2020}} to different states to help combat coronavirus. The [[Ministry of Home Affairs (India)|Ministry of Home Affairs]] approved {{INRConvert|11092|c|lk=on|year=2020}} for states as relief under the State Disaster Risk Management Fund.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/centre-grants-rs-17000cr-to-states-to-tackle-coronavirus-crisis/articleshow/74975956.cms|title=Centre grants Rs 17,000cr to states to tackle coronavirus crisis|last=|first=|date=4 April 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n*On '''6 April''' a 30% salary cut for one year was announced for the President, Vice President, Prime Minister, Governors, Members of Parliament and Ministers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/fighting-covid-19-pm-modi-ministers-mps-to-take-30-salary-cut-for-one-year/article31270019.ece|title=Fighting Covid-19: PM Modi, Ministers, MPs to take 30% salary cut for one year|last=|first=|date=6 April 2020|website=The Hindu @businessline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\":21\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/ordinance-passed-to-cut-salaries-of-mps-ministers-by-30-to-fund-covid-19-battle/story-2x9a6obfOxHc5HQ8rhS7FP.html|title=President, MPs, ministers take a pay cut for 1 year, say it is a message|date=2020-04-06|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> It was also decided to suspend the [[MPLADS]] for two years and transfer the money, about {{INRConvert|7900|c|lk=on|year=2020}}, into the [[Consolidated Fund of India|consolidated fund of India]].<ref name=\":21\" />\n*On '''8 April''' the Department of Expenditure, Finance Ministry, has allowed states net market borrowings of {{INRConvert|320481|c|lk=on|year=2020}} between April to December.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/finance/finance-ministry-allows-states-to-borrow-rs-3-20-lakh-crore-from-market/articleshow/75049770.cms|title=Finance Ministry allows states to borrow Rs 3.20 lakh crore from market|date=2020-04-08|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-09|url-status=live|agency=PTI}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/economy-finance/india-borrowing-plan-states-allowed-to-borrow-rs-32-lakh-crore-in-april-december|title=States Allowed To Borrow Rs 3.2 Lakh Crore in April-December|last=Ohri|first=Nikunj|date=8 April 2020|website=BloombergQuint|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> {{INRConvert|3000|c|lk=on|year=2020}} of funds under the [[Pradhan Mantri Garib Kalyan Yojana|PM Garib Kalyan Yojana]] have been given to over 20 million workers engaged in construction work by the various states and UTs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/coronavirus-lockdown-home-ministry-says-states-offer-rs-3-000-crore-funds-to-more-than-2-crore-const-2208530|title=Rs 3,000 Crore Given To 2 Crore Construction Workers By States: Centre|date=8 April 2020|website=NDTV|others=PTI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/productline/building-materials/rs-3000-crore-given-to-2-crore-registered-construction-workers-mha/articleshow/75060935.cms?from=mdr|title=Rs 3000 crore given to 2 crore registered construction workers: MHA|date=2020-04-09|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-09|url-status=live|agency=ANI}}</ref> To provide relief to tax payers amid the covid-19 crisis, the government will release {{INRConvert|18000|c|lk=on|year=2020}}.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Aulakh|first=Gulveen|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/wealth/personal-finance-news/govt-to-immediately-issue-rs-18000-crore-as-pending-tax-refunds-to-individuals-businesses/articleshow/75050023.cms|title=Govt to immediately issue Rs 18,000 crore as pending tax refunds to individuals, businesses|date=2020-04-08|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n*On '''10 April''' the [[Asian Development Bank]] assured India of {{INRConvert|15800|c|lk=on|year=2020}} assistance in the covid-19 outbreak fight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/covid-19-adb-assures-2-2-billion-package-for-india-11586496803375.html|title=Covid-19: ADB assures $2.2 billion package for India|last=Mishra|first=Asit Ranjan|date=2020-04-10|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n* On '''14 April''' at 10am the Prime Minister made a public speech in which he announced the extension of the nationwide lockdown, as well as a calibrated reopening. \"From the economy's point of view, the lockdown undoubtedly looks costly right now, but compared to the lives of Indian citizens, it is nothing\" ''(translation, original in Hindi).''<ref name=\":27\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/india/news/while-extending-indias-lockdown-modi-hinted-at-a-calibrated-re-opening-of-economy-say-experts/articleshow/75135600.cms|title=While extending India's lockdown Modi hinted at a calibrated re-opening of economy, say experts|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n*On '''15 April''' as part of the new lockdown 2.0 guidelines, the [[Ministry of Home Affairs (India)|Ministry of Home Affairs]] announced, among other things, that all agricultural and horticultural activities will remain fully functional.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.business-standard.com/multimedia/video-gallery/general/mha-issues-lockdown-2-0-guidelines-agricultural-horticultural-activities-to-remain-functional-102759.htm|title=MHA issues lockdown 2.0 guidelines: Agricultural, horticultural activities to remain functional|date=15 April 2020|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-15|url-status=live}}</ref> Information technology companies can function with 50% staff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/it-companies-allowed-to-function-with-50-staff-during-lockdown-2-0-11586926334442.html|title=IT companies allowed to function with 50% staff during lockdown 2.0|last=Agarwal|first=Nikhil|date=2020-04-15|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The partial lift of restrictions will take place from 20 April.<ref name=\":28\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52290761|title=India to allow farmers back to work amid lockdown|date=2020-04-15|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-16|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n*On '''17 April''', RBI announced more measures to counter the economic impact of the pandemic including {{INRConvert|50000|c|lk=on|year=2020}} special finance to [[National Bank for Agriculture and Rural Development|NABARD]], [[Small Industries Development Bank of India|SIDBI]], and [[National Housing Bank|NHB]].<ref name=\":30\" /> Providing more relief to state governments, WMA limits have been increased by 60 per cent.<ref name=\":30\" />\n\n=== COVID-19 Economic Response Task Force ===\nThe formation of the COVID-19 Economic Response Task Force was announced by Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] on 19 March 2020 during his live address to the nation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/government-forms-covid-19-economic-response-task-force-pm-modi/articleshow/74716284.cms|title=Covid 19 Economic Task Force: Government forms Covid-19 economic response task force, says PM Modi|last=|first=|date=19 March 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ddnews.gov.in/national/covid-19-task-force-deal-economic-challenges|title=COVID-19: Task Force to deal with economic challenges {{!}} DD News|website=ddnews.gov.in|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pm-narendra-modi-forms-economic-response-task-force-calls-for-janata-curfew/articleshow/74715013.cms?from=mdr|title=PM Narendra Modi forms economic response task force, calls for 'Janata Curfew'|date=2020-03-20|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> The task force is led by the finance minister [[Nirmala Sitharaman]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/coronavirus-impact-fm-led-economic-task-force-takes-stock-of-key-ministries/story/398804.html|title=Coronavirus in India: Economic task force yet to be formed; no decision on relief package|last=|first=|date=20 March 2020|website=Business Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> Though not formally constituted or no official date for relief packages being made, the consultation process with concerned parties has begun immediately.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/politics/policy/coronavirus-crisis-economic-package-to-be-announced-soon-says-sitharaman-11584722101953.html|title=Coronavirus crisis: Economic package to be announced soon, says Sitharaman|date=2020-03-20|website=Livemint|language=en|others=PTI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/health/subramanian-swamy-writes-to-pm-modi-over-covid-19-says-economic-relief-package-crucial/385273/|title=Subramanian Swamy writes to PM Modi over COVID-19, says economic relief package crucial|last=Nair|first=Remya|date=2020-03-21|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> There were concerns as to where will the government find the funds to fight coronavirus and keep the economy alive.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/where-will-modi-govt-get-money-to-fight-coronavirus-563-mn-fund-hopelessly-small/story/398918.html|title=Where will Modi govt find money to fight coronavirus? $563 mn fund hopelessly small|last=Dubey|first=Rajeev|date=23 March 2020|website=Business Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> Experts say the task force will have to look in to [[Non-performing Asset|NPA]] norms, tax payments and income support to those in the unorganised sectors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/coronavirus-impact-fm-led-economic-task-force-takes-stock-of-key-ministries/story/398804.html|title=Coronavirus in India: Economic task force yet to be formed; no decision on relief package|last=|first=|date=20 March 2020|website=Business Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> A direct cash transfer scheme for the most vulnerable is also being considered, as has happened in other countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbctv18.com/economy/coronavirus-task-force-to-meet-this-evening-to-work-on-relief-package-5522241.htm|title=Coronavirus task force to meet this evening to work on relief package|last=|first=|date=20 March 2020|website=CNBCTV18|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> The [[Ministry of Finance (India)|Ministry of Finance]] immediately started consultations with the RBI and ministries to take stock of most affected sectors like aviation, hospitality, and MSMEs.<ref name=\":1\" /> The [[ASSOCHAM|Associated Chambers of Commerce and Industry of India]] (ASSOCHAM), an apex [[Trade associations|trade association]] of [[India]] gave full support to the efforts.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Market|first=Capital|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-cm/assocham-to-share-ground-level-impact-on-coronavirus-with-economic-response-task-force-120032001822_1.html|title=ASSOCHAM To Share Ground Level Impact On Coronavirus With Economic Response Task Force|date=2020-03-20|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> On 24 March the Finance Minister made a number of announcements related to the economy with regard to the impact of COVID-19.<ref name=\":10\" /> On 26 March the Finance Minister announced more economic relief measures for the poor among other announcements.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\n== Economic situation ==\n[[File:Safe Newspaper Vendor - coronavirus.jpg|thumb|A newspaper vendor in [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]] wearing goggles, safety mask and hand gloves.]]\nIn India up to 53% of businesses have specified a certain amount of impact of shutdowns caused due to COVID-19 on operations ([[FICCI]] survey).<ref name=\":4\" /> Various business such as hotels and airlines are cutting salaries and laying off employees.<ref name=\":2\" /> Live events industry has seen an estimated loss of {{INRConvert|3000|c|lk=on|year=2020}}.<ref name=\":2\" /> A number of young startups have been impacted as funding has fallen.<ref name=\":15\" /> A DataLabs report shows a 45% decrease in the total growth-stage funding ([[Series A round]]) as compared to Q4 2019.<ref name=\":16\" /> On 4 April, former [[Reserve Bank of India]] chief [[Raghuram Rajan]] said that the coronavirus pandemic in India may just be the \"greatest emergency since Independence\".<ref name=\":22\" />\n\nNumerous companies are carrying out measures within their companies to ensure that staff anxiety is kept at a minimum. [[Hero MotoCorp|Hero Motocorp]] has been conducting video townhall meetings, [[Tata Group]] has set up a task force to make working from home more effective and the taskforce at [[Siemens]] also reports on the worldwide situation of the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Philip|first=Lijee|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/company/corporate-trends/india-inc-sets-up-task-forces-as-staff-anxiety-rises/articleshow/74853966.cms|title=India Inc sets up task forces as staff anxiety rises due to Covid-19 lockdown|date=2020-03-28|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-28|last2=Vijayraghavan|first2=Kala}}</ref>\n\nNight lights and economic activity are connected. In Delhi, night light [[radiance]] fell 37.2% compared to 1-31 March 2019. This was the biggest fall for any metro in India. Bangalore fell 32% while Mumbai dropped by 29%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/business/night-lights-tell-the-story-of-dimming-economic-activity-across-india|title=Night Lights Tell The Story Of Dimming Economic Activity Across India|last=Nahata|first=Pallavi|date=11 April 2020|website=BloombergQuint|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Agriculture ===\nDue to logistical problems following the lockdown tea estates were unable to harvest the [[First flush tea|first flush]]. The impact of this on the second flush is not known. The entire Darjeeling tea based tea industry will see significant fall in revenue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/agri-business/covid-19-lockdown-may-brew-trouble-for-tea-sector/article31199394.ece|title=Covid-19 lockdown may brew trouble for tea sector|last=Bose|first=Pratim Ranjan|date=29 March 2020|website=The Hindu @businessline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Tea exports could drop up to 8% as a result.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rakshit|first=Avishek|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/indian-tea-exports-may-decline-by-up-to-8-over-covid-19-outbreak-120040700782_1.html|title=Indian tea exports may decline by up to 8% over Covid-19 outbreak|date=2020-04-07|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nFrom 20 April, under the new lockdown guidelines to reopen the economy and relax the lockdown, agricultural businesses such as dairy, tea, coffee and rubber plantations, as well as associated shops and industries, will reopen.<ref name=\":28\" />\n\n=== Manufacturing ===\nMajor companies in India such as [[Larsen & Toubro|Larsen and Toubro]], [[Bharat Forge]], [[UltraTech Cement]], [[Grasim Industries]], the fashion and retail wing of [[Aditya Birla Group]], [[Tata Motors]] and [[Thermax]] have temporarily suspended or significantly reduced operations in a number of manufacturing facilities and factories across the country. Nearly all two-wheeler and four-wheeler companies have put a stop to production till further notice. Many companies have decided to remain closed till at least 31 March such as [[Cummins]] which has temporarily shut its offices across Maharashtra.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/industry/coronavirus-impact-india-inc-slips-into-sleep-mode/1908492/|title=Coronavirus impact: India Inc slips into sleep mode|last=|first=|date=25 March 2020|website=The Financial Express|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> [[Hindustan Unilever]], [[ITC Limited|ITC]] and [[Dabur India Limited|Dabur India]] have shut manufacturing facilities expect for factories producing essentials.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|last=Mudgill|first=Amit|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/how-will-india-lockdown-play-out-for-economy-markets-4-scenarios/articleshow/74804087.cms|title=How will India lockdown play out for economy & markets: 4 scenarios|date=2020-03-25|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> [[Foxconn]] and [[Wistron Corp.|Wistron Corp]], iPhone producers, have suspended production following the 21 days lockdown orders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-25/iphone-makers-suspend-india-production-due-to-lockdown|title=iPhone Makers Suspend India Production Due to Lockdown|last=Wu|first=Debby|date=25 March 2020|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n=== E-commerce ===\nIn the third week of March, [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] announced that it would stop sale of non-essential items in India so that it can focus on essential needs.<ref name=\":8\" /> Amazon has followed the same strategy in Italy and France.<ref name=\":8\" /> On 25 March, [[Walmart]]-owned [[Flipkart]] temporarily suspended some of its services on its e-commerce platform and will only be selling and distributing essentials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gadgets.ndtv.com/internet/news/flipkart-services-suspended-india-coronavirus-lockdown-walmart-2200237|title=Flipkart Suspends Services as India Enters 21-Day Coronavirus Lockdown|last=Sarwar|first=Nadeem|date=25 March 2020|website=NDTV Gadgets 360|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> BigBasket and [[Grofers]] also run restricted services, facing disruptions in services due to the lockdown.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shrivastava|first=Aditi|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/newsbuzz/despite-govt-clearance-ecomm-cos-find-it-difficult-to-deliver-essentials/articleshow/74803036.cms|title=Despite govt clearance, ecomm cos find it difficult to deliver essentials|date=2020-03-25|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-26|last2=Peermohamed|first2=Alnoor}}</ref> [[Delhi Police]] began issuing delivery agents curfew passes to make it easier for them to keep the supply chain open.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/have-issued-passes-e-commerce-websites-delivery-agents-will-be-helped-delhi-police-11585129545453.html|title=Have issued passes, e-commerce websites' delivery agents will be helped: Police|date=2020-03-25|editor-last=Jagannath|editor-first=J.|website=Livemint|language=en|others=IANS|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> E-commerce companies also look for legal clarity related to what are \"essentials\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Peermohamed|first=Alnoor|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/newsbuzz/covid-19-harried-etailers-look-to-deliver-the-goods/articleshow/74820615.cms|title=Covid-19: Amazon, Flipkart, others look to deliver the goods|date=2020-03-26|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Stock markets ===\nOn 23 March 2020''',''' stock markets in India post worst losses in history.<ref name=\":3\" /> [[BSE SENSEX|SENSEX]] fell 4000 points (13.15%) and [[NIFTY 50|NSE NIFTY]] fell 1150 points (12.98%).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/sensex-hits-10-lower-circuit-what-led-to-the-market-meltdown/articleshow/74768152.cms|title=Sensex crashes 4,000 points: What's behind market meltdown|date=2020-03-23|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> However, on 25 March, one day after a complete 21 day lock-down was announced by the Prime Minister, [[SENSEX]] posted its biggest gains in 11 years, adding a value of  {{INRConvert|4.7|lc|lk=on|year=2020}} crore for investors.<ref name=\":11\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/tech/flipkart-to-resume-shipping-and-deliveries-from-later-today-confirms-ceo-2550957.html|title=Flipkart to Resume Shipping and Deliveries from Later Today, Confirms CEO|last=Das|first=Shouvik|date=2020-03-25|website=News18|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> On 8 April, following positive indication from the Wall Street that the pandemic may have reached its peak in the US, the stock markets in India rose steeply once again.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/markets/market-live-markets-sensex-nifty-bse-nse-sgx-nifty-coronavirus-120040900142_1.html|title=MARKET LIVE: Sensex leaps 1,000 pts, Nifty past 9k; auto stocks rally|last=|first=|date=9 April 2020|website=Business Standard|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/stock-market/news/indian-stock-market-sensex-and-nifty-updates-april-9-2020/articleshow/75058871.cms|title=Indian stock market indices rally over 3% amidst positive cues from global markets|last=Yadav|first=Navdeep|date=9 April 2020|website=Business Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n=== Estimate of economic losses ===\nThe Indian economy is expected to lose over {{INRConvert|32000|c|lk=on|year=2020}} every day during the first 21 days of the lockdown, according to [[SME Rating Agency of India|Acuit\u00e9 Ratings]], a RBI approved [[credit rating agency]].<ref name=\":23\" /> [[Barclays]] said the cost of the first 21 days of shutdown as well as the previous two shorter ones will be total to around {{INRConvert|8.5|lc|lk=on|year=2020}}.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":24\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/experts-peg-indias-cost-of-coronavirus-lockdown-at-usd-120-bn/article31160115.ece|title=Experts peg India's cost of coronavirus lockdown at USD 120 bn|last=PTI|date=25 March 2020|website=The Hindu @businessline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> \n\nOn 27 March, [[Moody's Investors Service]] downgraded its estimate of India's GDP growth for 2020 from 5.3% to 2.5%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/coronavirus-moodys-cuts-india-2020-gdp-growth-forecast-to-2-point-5-percent/story/399377.html|title=Coronavirus: Moody's cuts India's 2020 GDP growth forecast to 2.5%|date=27 March 2020|website=Business Today|others=PTI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> [[Fitch Ratings]] revised its estimate for India's growth to 2%. India Ratings & Research also downgraded the FY21 estimate to 3.6%.<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/business/world-bank-sees-fy21-india-growth-at-15-28-slowest-since-economic-reforms-30-years-ago/article31322011.ece|title=World Bank sees FY21 India growth at 1.5-2.8%, slowest since economic reforms 30 years ago|date=2020-04-12|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-13|others=PTI|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> On 12 April 2020, a [[World Bank]] report focusing on South Asia said that India's economy is expected to grow 1.5% to 2.8% for FY21.<ref name=\":25\" /> This will be the lowest growth for India in 30 years.<ref name=\":26\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/covid-19-causes-severe-disruption-to-indian-economy-says-world-bank/articleshow/75104070.cms|title=World Bank sees FY21 India growth at 1.5-2.8%\u2014 slowest since economic reforms three decades ago|last=|first=|date=12 April 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The World Bank report said that the pandemic has \"magnified pre-existing risks to India\u2019s economic outlook\".<ref name=\":25\" />\n\n[[Confederation of Indian Industry]] (CII) has sought an economic [[Stimulus (economics)|fiscal stimulus]] package of 1% of India's GDP amounting to {{INRConvert|2|lc|lk=on|year=2020}}.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/india-inc-seeks-fiscal-stimulus-moratorium-on-debt-repayment-to-mitigate-coronavirus-impact/articleshow/74759967.cms|title=India Inc seeks fiscal stimulus, moratorium on debt repayment to mitigate coronavirus impact|date=2020-03-22|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-23|url-status=live|agency=PTI}}</ref> The fiscal package and fiscal policies approach is being compared to what has happened in other countries such as Germany, Brazil and Japan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/economy/interview-india-economic-package-coronavirus|title=India Should Have Already Announced an Economic Package for Coronavirus|last=Srivas|first=Anuj|date=22 March 2020|website=The Wire|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> [[Jefferies Group]] said that the government can spend {{INRConvert|1.3|lc|lk=on|year=2020}} to fight the impact of coronavirus.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-govt-can-spend-18-billion-to-fight-virus-impact-analysts-say-11584949476261.html|title=Coronavirus: Govt can spend $18 billion to fight virus impact, analysts say|date=2020-03-23|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg's]] economists say at least {{INRConvert|2.15|lc|lk=on|year=2020}} needs to be spent.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nIt is estimated that the loss to the tourism industry will be {{INRConvert|15000|c|lk=on|year=2020}} for March and April alone. [[Confederation of Indian Industry|CII]], [[ASSOCHAM]] and FAITH estimate that a huge chunk of the workforce involved with tourism in the country faces unemployment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/nirmala-sitharaman-reviews-sectors-that-may-need-intervention/story-KhFNT5NejEDB4F3K8RPM0H.html|title=Nirmala Sitharaman reviews sectors that may need intervention|last=Jayaswal|first=Rajeev|date=2020-03-21|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n== Concerns and commentary ==\n[[Adar Poonawalla]], CEO of [[Serum Institute of India]] said that \"the economic danger of the outbreak was exponentially greater than its health risks,\" as reported in Economic Times.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/healthcare/biotech/healthcare/coronavirus-vaccine-within-a-year-but-it-wont-be-100-effective/articleshow/74704452.cms?from=mdr|title=Coronavirus vaccine within a year but it won't be 100% effective|date=2020-03-20|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> There are concerns as to where will the government find the funds to fight coronavirus and keep the economy alive.<ref name=\":0\" /> [[Subramanian Swamy]] tweeted on 21 March 2020 asking whether declaration of an financial emergency was inevitable (in the light of the situation because of the coronavirus pandemic).<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n=== Supply chains and logistics ===\nFollowing the lockdown certain essential supply chains broke down.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.unifiedinfotech.net/blog/how-covid-19-changed-ecommerce/|title=Pandemic effect: how Covid-19 changed ecommerce and supply chain industry|date=2020-03-23|work=Unified Infotech|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> [[Britannia Industries]], supporting the lockdown, urged the government to ensure inter-state movement of the raw material for the food processing industry was not hampered. The [[Managing director|Managing Director]] of Britannia stated that \"if even one link in the supply chain is broken, the country could run out of stocks of packaged food in the next 7-10 days.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/cons-products/fmcg/lockdown-britannia-urges-govt-to-issue-necessary-permits-to-people-in-food-processing-supply-chain/articleshow/74825647.cms|title=Lockdown: Britannia urges govt to issue necessary permits to people in food processing supply chain|date=2020-03-26|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Although inter-state travel has been banned, it doesn't apply to essentials, and in places like [[Maharashtra]] the state police is yet to streamline the process, causing a disruption to supply chains.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/coronavirus-outbreak-in-maharashtra-police-disrupting-farm-produce-supply-chains-impairs-farmers-lack-of-labour-stalls-harvest-8193061.html|title=Coronavirus Outbreak: In Maharashtra, police disrupting farm produce supply chains impairs farmers, lack of labour stalls harvest|last=MN|first=Parth|date=26 March 2020|website=Firstpost|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Vidya Krishnan writes in [[The Atlantic]] that due to the lockdown even movement of medical goods were affected.<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2020/03/india-coronavirus-covid19-narendra-modi/608896/|title=The Callousness of India's COVID-19 Response|last=Krishnan|first=Vidya|date=2020-03-27|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March the government allowed the movement of all essential as well as non-essential goods across the country during the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown]].<ref name=\":13\" /> The milk and newspaper supply chains are also allowed to function.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\n=== Salaries ===\nThe Prime Minister on 19 March urged businesses and high income segments of society to take care of the economic needs of all those who provide them services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/|title=Business News Today, Stock Market News, Sensex & Finance News|last=Mishra|first=Asit Ranjan|date=19 March 2020|website=Livemint|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> During the live telecast he also appealed to families to not cut the pay of [[domestic help]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/india/news/modi-appeals-people-to-not-cut-the-pay-of-domestic-help-and-others-who-cant-come-to-work/articleshow/74716721.cms|title=Modi appeals people to not cut the pay of domestic help and others who can't come to work|last=Sindwani|first=Prerna|date=20 March 2020|website=Business Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Following the lockdown, the government circulated advisories<ref>Joint Secretary (20 March 2020) [https://labour.gov.in/sites/default/files/Central_Government_Update.pdf Advisory]. Ministry of Labour and Employment, Government of India. Retrieved on 4 April 2020.</ref> and directives ordering companies to keep paying employees among other things.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/company/corporate-trends/how-do-we-keep-paying-wages-wonders-stricken-industry/articleshow/74940685.cms|title=How do we keep paying wages, wonders stricken industry|date=2020-04-02|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/money/unable-to-join-office-ministry-of-labour-and-employment-issues-advisory-to-employers-amidst-coronavirus-crisis/1906909/|title=Concerned about pay cut, losing job amid Coronavirus crisis? Labour Ministry issues advisory to employers|date=2020-03-23|website=The Financial Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The [[Ministry of Finance (India)|Ministry of Finance]] issued an Office Memorandum on 23 March 2020:<ref name=\":18\" /><ref>Additional Secretary to the Govt of India, Department of Expenditure (23 March 2020) [https://doe.gov.in/sites/default/files/Payment%20of%20Wages%20to%20Outsourced_Contractual%20Staff%20-%20COVID%2019.pdf Office Memorandum]. Ministry of Finance. Retrieved on 4 April 2020.</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=[...] wherever such contractual, the casual and outsourced staff of Ministries/Departments and other organization of Government of India is required to stay at home in view of lockdown order regarding COVID-19 prevention [...] they shall be treated as \"on duty\" during such period of absence and necessary pay/wages would be paid accordingly. [...] <br/>These instructions shall apply until April 30, 2020.|author=Addt Sect, Dept of Expenditure, Ministry of Finance|title=|source=}}\n\nA few days later worries grew as to how wages could continue being paid and if the directive was legal or not.<ref name=\":17\" /> There were also concerns raised by migrant workers regarding implementation of the orders as many daily-wagers have no records of being sacked or salaries being paid or deducted; the concerns also expand to uncertainty in the government's ability to enforce minimum wages under a lockdown when it couldn't even do so during normal times.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/migrants-question-implementation-of-govt-advisory-on-protecting-wages-jobs/story-bSJcx1l7ODCA1qgUBnG6qJ.html|title=Migrants question implementation advisory on protecting wages, jobs|last=Dey|first=Abhishek|date=2020-04-01|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Migrant workers and labour force ===\nDue to the lockdown, there suddenly was no work for many daily workers (the urban poor and migrant labourers). At the same time the lockdown restrictions put a stop on the movement of buses and trains. Large numbers of migrant workers ended up walking back to there villages, some journeys hundreds of kilometers long. Commentators commented on how the whole purpose of social distancing was defeated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/global-economics/india-s-government-should-have-expected-coronavirus-migration|title=Coronavirus Exposes India's Official Callousness|last=Sharma|first=Mihir|date=1 April 2020|website=BloombergQuint|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref name=\":19\" />\n\nSoon after a central government directive in late March, state governments set up 21,000 camps to house over 660,000 migrants and stop the exodus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/more-than-21000-camps-set-up-for-over-660000-migrants-state-governments/articleshow/74920798.cms|title=More than 21,000 camps set up for over 6,60,000 migrants: State governments|date=2020-04-01|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Delhi government is providing free food to 400,000 people every day.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/coronavirus-delhi-to-feed-4-lakh-people-from-tomorrow-ready-for-even-1000-cases-a-day-says-kejriwal/article31180118.ece|title=Coronavirus {{!}} Delhi govt to feed 4 lakh people from tomorrow; ready for even 1,000 cases a day, says Kejriwal|date=2020-03-27|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-03|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> Over 500 hunger relief centres have been set by the Delhi government.<ref name=\":20\" />\n\nBy 5 April, 75,00,000 people were being provided food across the country in government and NGO food camps.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/nation/over-75-lakh-being-fed-at-food-camps-mha-66223|title=Over 75 lakh being fed at food camps: MHA|date=6 April 2020|work=The Tribune|access-date=12 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Lockdown extension ===\nOn 8 April 2020, the managing director of [[Bajaj Auto]], [[Rajiv Bajaj]], wrote in an opinion piece in the [[The Economic Times|Economic Times]] that the \"lockdown makes India weak rather than stronger in combating the epidemic,\" and that the current \"arbitrary\" lockdown was totally unsustainable and a \"recalibration\" is needed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/business/coronavirus-lockdown-makes-india-weak-rather-than-stronger-rajiv-bajaj-writes-in-et|title=Coronavirus Lockdown Makes India Weak Rather Than Stronger, Rajiv Bajaj Writes In ET|website=BloombergQuint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/view-must-sell-ourselves-out-of-this-crisis/articleshow/75038503.cms|title=India may have to sell itself out of this crisis, says Rajiv Bajaj|date=2020-04-08|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Rajiv Bajaj writes that \"India may have to sell itself out of the coronavirus crisis\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://auto.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/industry/india-may-have-to-sell-itself-out-of-this-crisis-says-rajiv-bajaj/75058899|title=India may have to sell itself out of this crisis, says Rajiv Bajaj - ET Auto|last=|first=|date=9 April 2020|website=ETAuto|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the extension of the lockdown on 14 April, members of the opposition said that there was no mention of a financial package or any steps whatsoever to revive the economy.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/congress-says-pm-modis-address-hollow-no-mention-of-financial-package/article31336629.ece|title=Congress says PM Modi\u2019s address 'hollow', no mention of financial package|date=2020-04-14|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-14|url-status=live|agency=PTI|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> Modi however did talk about a re-calibrated opening of the economy.<ref name=\":27\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* Suvojit Chattopadhyay (27 March 2020). [https://qz.com/india/1826705/modis-coronavirus-relief-package-will-work-if-distributed-fairly/ India\u2019s $23 billion coronavirus relief package will help only if it reaches those in need]. [[Quartz India]]\n* Soutik Biswas (30 March 2020). [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52086274 Coronavirus: India's pandemic lockdown turns into a human tragedy]. BBC\n* Arunoday Mukharji (3 April 2020). [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52117704 Coronavirus: India's bailout may not be enough to save economy]. BBC\n*Pallavi Nahata (13 April 2020). [https://www.bloombergquint.com/business/in-charts-the-emerging-economic-impact-of-a-nationwide-lockdown In Charts: The Emerging Economic Impact Of A Nationwide Lockdown]. [[BloombergQuint]] {{Locked content}} \n*Shivani Sharma, Mohsin Shaikh \u00a0(17 April 2020). [https://www.businesstoday.in/current/graphics/infographic-coronavirus-india-economy/story/401325.html Infographic: How coronavirus has hurt Indian economy]. [[Business Today (India)|Business Today<br />]]\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Impact of COVID-19 in the economy of India}}\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in India|Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\nThe '''economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in India''' has been hugely disruptive. [[World Bank]] and [[Credit rating agency|credit rating agencies]] have downgraded India's growth for [[fiscal year]] 2021 with the lowest figures India has seen in three decades since India's [[Economic liberalisation in India|economic liberalization in the 1990s]].<ref name=\":25\" /><ref name=\":26\" /> However, the [[International Monetary Fund]] projection for India for the [[Financial Year|financial year]] 2021-22 of 1.9% GDP growth is the highest among [[G20|G-20]] nations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/business/story/rbi-governor-shaktikanta-das-indian-economy-covid19-imf-projection-gdp-growth-1667889-2020-04-17|title=IMF projection for India\u2019s GDP growth highest in G-20, says RBI Governor Shaktikanta Das|last=|first=|date=17 April 2020|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Indian economy]] is expected to lose over {{INRConvert|32000|c|lk=on|year=2020}} every day during the first [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|21-days of complete lockdown]] which was declared following the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India|coronavirus outbreak]].<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/covid-19-lockdown-estimated-to-cost-india-45-billion-a-day-acuit-ratings/article31235264.ece|title=Covid-19 lockdown estimated to cost India $4.5 billion a day: Acuit\u00e9 Ratings|last=|first=|date=2 April 2020|website=The Hindu Business Line|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref name=\":24\" /> Under complete lockdown less than a quarter of India's $2.8 trillion economy is functional.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/policy/economy/news/lockdown-relaxation-more-than-half-of-indian-economy-may-reopen-from-monday-april-20/articleshow/75220299.cms|title=Lockdown relaxation\u2060\u2014 more than half of India's economy may reopen from Monday, says Nomura|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> Up to 53% of businesses in the country will be significantly affected.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/companies/news/coronavirus-impact-indian-industry-seeks-relief-measures-to-aid-economy-11584904435575.html|title=Coronavirus impact: Indian industry seeks relief measures to aid economy|last=Biman.Mukherji|date=2020-03-23|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> [[Supply chain]]s have been put under stress with the lockdown restrictions in place; initially there was a lack of clarity in streamlining what is an \"essential\" and what isn't.<ref name=\"Chaudhry\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/agri-business/covid-19-puts-indias-food-supply-chain-to-a-stress-test/article31173973.ece|title=Covid-19 puts India's food supply chain to a stress-test|last=Chaudhry|first=Siraj A.|date=26 March 2020|website=The Hindu @businessline|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Those in the informal sectors and daily wage groups are the most at risk.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/136-million-jobs-at-risk-in-post-corona-india-11585584169192.html|title=136 million jobs at risk in post-corona India|last=Das|first=Goutam|date=2020-03-30|website=Livemint|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> A large number of farmers around the country who grow [[Perishable food|perishables]] are also facing uncertainty.<ref name=\"Chaudhry\" /> Various businesses such as hotels and airlines are cutting salaries and laying off employees.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Goyal|first=Malini|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/finance/covid-19-crisis-how-the-deadly-virus-hints-at-a-looming-financial-crisis/articleshow/74752200.cms|title=Covid-19: How the deadly virus hints at a looming financial crisis|date=2020-03-22|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The live events industry has seen an estimated loss of {{INRConvert|3000|c|lk=on|year=2020}}.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nMajor companies in India such as [[Larsen & Toubro|Larsen and Toubro]], [[Bharat Forge]], [[UltraTech Cement]], [[Grasim Industries]], [[Aditya Birla Group]], [[Tata Motors]] and [[Thermax]] have temporarily suspended or significantly reduced operations. [[iPhone]] producing companies in India have also suspended a majority of operations. Young startups have been impacted as [[Venture capital financing|funding]] has fallen.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/young-indian-startups-hit-as-investors-get-cautious/1787866|title=Young Indian startups hit as investors get cautious|date=1 April 2020|website=Outlook India|others=IANS|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://inc42.com/datalab/pandemic-impacts-funding-prospects-for-startups-after-slow-q1-2020|title=Covid-19 Pandemic Spoils Indian Startup Funding Party, Growth Stage Worst Hit In Q1 2020|last=Singh|first=Sandeep|date=2020-04-01|website=Inc42 Media|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In the third week of March, [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] and [[Walmart]]-owned [[Flipkart]] announced that it would stop sale of non-essential items in India so that it could focus on essential deliveries.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/amazon-to-stop-non-essential-sales-in-india-2200154|title=Amazon To Stop Non-Essential Sales In India|date=24 March 2020|website=NDTV|others=Reuters|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Other fast-moving consumer goods companies in the country have significantly reduced operations and are focusing on essentials. Stock markets in [[India]] posted their worst loses in history on 23 March 2020.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/business/market/bse-sensex-nse-nifty-stock-market-live-updates-coronavirus-global-markets-6327415/|title=Stock markets post worst losses in history; Sensex crashes 3,935 points amid coronavirus lockdown|date=2020-03-23|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> However, on 25 March, one day after a complete [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|21 day lockdown]] was announced by the Prime Minister, [[SENSEX]] and [[NIFTY 50|NIFTY]] posted their biggest gains in 11 years, adding a value of  {{INRConvert|4.7|lc|lk=on|year=2020}} crore to investor wealth.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|last=Shah|first=Ami|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/sensex-logs-biggest-one-day-gain-in-11-years-investors-richer-by-rs-4-7-lakh-crore/articleshow/74810933.cms|title=Sensex posts biggest gain in 11 years: Investors richer by Rs 4.7 lakh crore|date=2020-03-25|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n{{Quote box\n| quote = \"From the economy's point of view, the lockdown undoubtedly looks costly right now, but compared to the lives of Indian citizens, it is nothing.\" ''(translation, original in Hindi)''\n| author = Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]], speech to the nation, 10 am, 14 April 2020.\n| source = <ref>{{cite news |title=Economic cost of lockdown is nothing compared to people's lives: PM Modi |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/economic-cost-of-lockdown-is-nothing-compared-to-people-s-lives-pm-modi-120041400359_1.html |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=Business Standard |agency=ANI |date=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Lockdown hurts economy but saving life is more important: PM Modi |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/lockdown-hurts-economy-but-saving-lives-is-more-important-pm-modi-1666725-2020-04-14 |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=India Today |date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n| width = 300px\n| fontsize = 110%\n}}\nThe [[Government of India]] has announced a variety of measures to tackle the situation, from [[food security]] and extra funds for healthcare, to sector related incentives and tax deadline extensions. On 27 March the [[Reserve Bank of India]] also announced a number of measures which would make available {{INRConvert|374000|c|lk=on|year=2020}} to the country's financial system. On 29 March the government allowed the movement of all essential as well as non-essential goods during the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown]].<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/covid-19-govt-allows-transportation-of-all-essential-non-essential-goods-120033000055_1.html|title=Covid-19: Govt allows transportation of all essential, non-essential goods|date=2020-03-30|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-03-30|url-status=live|agency=PTI}}</ref> On 1 April, [[World Bank]] approved $1 bn in support to India to tackle the coronavirus pandemic. On 3 April the central government released more funds to the states for tackling the coronavirus totalling to {{INRConvert|28379|c|lk=on|year=2020}}. On 6 April a 30% salary cut for one year was announced for the President, Prime Minister and Members of Parliament.<ref name=\":21\" />\n\nOn 14 April 2020, the Prime Minister of India extended the lockdown to 3 May. A new set of guidelines for the calibrated opening of the economy and relaxation of the lockdown were also set in place which will take effect from 20 April.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sharma|first=Aman|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/india-evolves-worlds-largest-smart-model-0f-lockdown-officials/articleshow/75169336.cms|title=India evolves world\u2019s largest smart model of lockdown: Officials|date=2020-04-16|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> On 17 April, the [[RBI Governor]] announced more measures to counter the economic impact of the pandemic including {{INRConvert|50000|c|lk=on|year=2020}} special finance to [[National Bank for Agriculture and Rural Development|NABARD]], [[Small Industries Development Bank of India|SIDBI]], and [[National Housing Bank|NHB]].<ref name=\":30\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/economy/rbi-governor-shaktikanta-das-live-news-updates-fiscal-stimulus-monetary-policy-economic-relief-coronavirus/1931155/|title=RBI Governor Highlights: Shaktikanta Das cuts reverse repo; pumps in money, liquidity; eases rules for banks, NBFCs|date=2020-04-17|website=The Financial Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March the [[Press Information Bureau]] brought out a fact check that stories about a financial emergency being imposed in India are fake.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/stop-panicking-pm-modi-is-not-declaring-an-emergency-stay-away-from-fake-news/articleshow/74791920.cms|title=Stop Panicking: PM Modi is not declaring an emergency; Stay Away from Fake News|last=|first=|date=24 March 2020|website=Mumbai Mirror|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> A [[Financial Emergency in India|financial emergency]] has never been imposed in the history of India as yet.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2020/03/21/is-declaration-of-economic-emergency-inevitable-asks-subramanian-swamy.html|title=Is declaration of economic emergency inevitable, asks Subramanian Swamy|last=|first=|date=21 March 2020|website=The Week|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> On 4 April, former RBI chief [[Raghuram Rajan]] said that the coronavirus pandemic in India may just be the \"greatest emergency since Independence\".<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/greatest-emergency-since-independence-rbi-chief-raghuram-rajan-on-covid-19-2206716|title=\"Greatest Emergency Since Independence\": Raghuram Rajan On COVID-19|last=Ghosh|first=Deepshikha|date=6 April 2020|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n== Lives versus livelihood debate ==\n\n=== 24 March: ''Jaan hai toh jahaan hai'' (only if there is life there will be livelihood)  ===\nPrime Minister Modi announced the first 21 days of India's lockdown on 24 March. During this address to the nation he had said, \"''Jaan Hai Toh Jahaan Hai'' (only if there is life there will be livelihood)\".<ref name=\":29\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/modi-says-jaan-bhi-jahaan-bhi-signals-a-shift-in-india-s-coronavirus-playbook-11586606578037.html|title=Modi says \u2018jaan bhi jahaan bhi', signals a shift in India\u2019s coronavirus playbook|last=Khanna|first=Utpal Bhaskar,Anuja,Pretika|date=2020-04-11|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/opinion/columns/new-delhi-revisits-the-lives-versus-livelihood-debate-11586710892651.html|title=Opinion {{!}} New Delhi revisits the lives versus livelihood debate|last=Padmanabhan|first=Anil|date=2020-04-12|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n=== 11 April: ''Jaan bhi jahaan bhi'' (both lives and livelihood matter equally)  ===\nOn 11 April, in a meeting with the Chief Ministers of India, he said \"Our mantra earlier was ''jaan hai toh jahaan hai'' but now it is ''jaan bhi jahaan bhi'' (both, lives and livelihood matter equally).\"<ref name=\":29\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/pm-modi-s-meeting-with-chief-ministers-five-things-to-watch-out-for-11586576286173.html|title=PM Modi's meeting with chief ministers: Five things to watch out for|last=Varma,Anuja|first=Gyan|date=2020-04-11|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> On 14 April, another address to the nation was made by Modi in which he extended the lockdown, with adjustments, to 3 May.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/opinion/indias-lockdown-2-can-cost-as-many-lives-as-it-saves/402269/|title=No matter how you look at it, India\u2019s lockdown-2 can cost as many lives as it will save|last=Yadav|first=Yogendra|date=2020-04-15|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== Government actions ==\n\n=== Timeline ===\n\n* On '''21 March 2020''', the [[Union cabinet|Union Cabinet]] approved incentives worth {{INRConvert|40995|c|lk=on|year=2020}} for electronic manufacturing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/business/cabinet-approves-production-linked-incentives-for-electronics-manufacturing-firms-2|title=Cabinet Approves Production-Linked Incentives For Electronics Manufacturing Firms|date=|website=BloombergQuint|language=en|others=PTI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Phartiyal|first=Sankalp|url=https://in.reuters.com/article/india-electronics-idINKBN2190JJ|title=India lays out $6 billion roadmap to boost electronics manufacturing|date=2020-03-22|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-23|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref>\n*Various state governments have announced financial assistance for the poor in the unorganised sector. On '''21 March''' the [[Government of Uttar Pradesh|Uttar Pradesh government]] decided to give a direct money transfer of {{INRConvert|1000||lk=|year=2020}} to all daily wage laborers in the state<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/yogi-adityanath-announces-relief-measures-for-ups-daily-wage-earners/articleshow/74744711.cms|title=Yogi Adityanath announces relief measures for UP's daily wage earners|author=|website=Economic times}}</ref> and the following day [[Punjab]] announced {{INRConvert|3000||lk=|year=2020}} each for all registered construction workers in state.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chandigarh/coronavirus-rs-3000-relief-for-construction-workers-says-punjab-cm-amarinder-singh/articleshow/74754595.cms|title=Coronavirus: Rs 3,000 relief for construction workers, says Punjab CM Amarinder Singh|date=22 March 2020|work=The Times of India|accessdate=22 March 2020|agency=TNN}}</ref> On '''23 March''' it was announced that Haryana labourers, street vendors and rickshaw pullers will be provided an assistance of \u20b91,000 per week directly deposited into their bank accounts. [[Below Poverty Line]] families will be provided rations (including rice, wheat, mustard oil, sugar) free of cost for the month of April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/chandigarh/all-15-haryana-dists-locked-down-financial-support-announced-for-the-poor/story-yguH21C7I59Sj7G8oIweJL.html|title=All 15 Haryana dists locked down, financial support announced for the poor|date=2020-03-23|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n* On '''24 March''', in his address to the nation, the Prime Minister announced a {{INRConvert|15000|c|lk=on|year=2020}} fund for the healthcare sector.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/india/pm-declares-21-day-full-lockdown-across-india-from-midnight-rs-15000-cr-to-fight-covid-19/387457/|title=PM declares 21-day full lockdown across India from midnight, Rs 15,000 cr to fight COVID-19|last=Chandna|first=Himani|last2=Basu|first2=Mohana|date=24 March 2020|website=ThePrint|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n* On '''24 March''' at 2:30pm, the Finance Minister made a number of announcements related to the economy such as extending last dates for filing [[Goods and Services Tax (India)|GST]] returns and income tax returns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/finance-minister-nirmala-sitharaman-live-updates-coronavirus-outbreak-india-economic-package-announcement-media-briefing-news-today-8182241.html|title=FM Nirmala Sitharaman on Coronavirus Outbreak LIVE Updates: Firms with less than Rs 5 cr turnover, no interest, penalty, late fee on late GST return filing|website=Firstpost|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>  The due dates for the Sabka Vishwas (Legacy Dispute Resolution) Scheme 2019, customs clearances and for compliance matters under the Customs Act and associated laws has been extended to June 2020.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://mercomindia.com/finance-ministry-economic-relief-measures-coronavirus-outbreak/|title=Finance Ministry Announces Economic Relief Measures Amid Coronavirus Outbreak|last=Parikh|first=Anjana|date=2020-03-24|website=Mercom India|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n* On '''25 March''' the [[Modi government]] announced the world's largest [[food security]] scheme for 80 crore (800,000,000 people) across the country.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/economy/modi-govts-largest-ration-subsidy-scheme-for-80-cr-indians-buy-rice-wheat-at-this-price/1909103/|title=Modi govt's largest ration subsidy scheme for 80 Cr Indians; check full details of govt plan|last=Sharma|first=Samrat|date=25 March 2020|website=The Financial Express|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Cabinet Minister [[Prakash Javadekar]] made the announcement in a press conference that the ration would be 7&nbsp;kg every month (which includes wheat at a cost of {{INRConvert|2||lk=on|year=2020}} per kg and rice at  {{INRConvert|3||lk=on|year=2020}} per kg.)<ref name=\":9\" />\n* On '''25 March''' the Uttar Pradesh government banned the manufacture and sale of [[pan masala]], stating in the order that \"Spitting pan masala can help in spreading Covid-19\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/up-govt-bans-manufacture-sale-of-pan-masala-to-fight-coronavirus-spread-11585140181755.html|title=UP govt bans manufacture, sale of pan masala to fight coronavirus spread|date=2020-03-25|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Following this, other states such as Andhra Pradesh, Rajasthan and Gujarat also banned spitting in public places.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_in/article/pkev9m/gujarat-banned-spitting-to-stop-coronavirus|title=It Took Coronavirus for an Indian State to Ban Spitting in Public|last=Solani|first=Dhvani|date=2020-03-16|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/coronavirus-groups-hail-ban-on-spitting-in-rajasthan/article31319937.ece|title=Coronavirus {{!}} Groups hail ban on spitting in Rajasthan|date=2020-04-11|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-13|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/andhra-pradesh/2020/apr/12/andhra-pradesh-government-bans-spitting-in-public-places-2129100.html|title=Andhra Pradesh government bans spitting in public places|last=|first=|date=12 April 2020|website=The New Indian Express|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n*On '''26 March''' the Finance Minister announced a number of economic relief measures for the poor. {{INRConvert|170000|c|lk=on|year=2020}} will fund the [[Pradhan Mantri Garib Kalyan Yojana]] which will provide both cash transfer and food security; with the aim that no one goes hungry amidst the lockdown.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/fm-nirmala-sitharaman-announces-rs-1-7-lakh-crore-relief-package-for-poor/articleshow/74825054.cms|title=FM Nirmala Sitharaman announces Rs 1.7 lakh crore relief package for poor|date=2020-03-26|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> [[Pradhan Mantri Ujjwala Yojana]] beneficiaries will get free cylinders for at least three months. This will benefit over 8 crore [[Below Poverty Line|below poverty line]] families.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/business/story/finance-minister-nirmala-sitharaman-live-updates-economic-relief-package-india-coronavirus-1659912-2020-03-26|title=Coronavirus: FM Sitharaman announces package worth Rs 1,70,000 crore for poor, daily wagers|last=|first=|date=26 March 2020|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>  The government will expedite payment of the first instalment (\u20b92,000) due in 2020\u201321 in April itself under the Pradhan Mantri Kisan Samman Nidhi (PM-KISAN). For the organised sector worker, the government will pay the Employees\u2019 Provident Fund (EPF) contributions of both sides for 80 lakh employees of small companies who earn up to \u20b915,000 a month.The raise in the threshold from \u20b91lakh to \u20b91crore for triggering insolvency proceedings under the Insolvency and Bankruptcy Code (IBC) will help MSMEs. State governments were given various instructions and guidelines such as diverting district mineral funds for health needs relating to the pandemic.<ref name=\":12\" />\n*On '''26 March''' India participated in the virtual 'Extraordinary G20 Leaders\u2019 Summit'. The G20 nations decided to inject over $5 trillion into the global economy to counteract the pandemic's impacts. They agreed to work together, to strengthen the World Health Organisation, develop a vaccine and make it available. They decided to share timely and transparent information, materials for research and development and data. Besides expanding manufacturing capacity for medical supplies, they agreed to ensure smooth flows of critical supplies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/business/g20-leaders-pledge-usd-5-trillion-united-response-to-coronavirus-crisis/articleshow/74835666.cms|title=G20 leaders pledge USD 5 trillion, 'united' response to coronavirus crisis|date=2020-03-26|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref>[https://g20.org/en/media/Documents/G20_Extraordinary%20G20%20Leaders%E2%80%99%20Summit_Statement_EN%20(3).pdf G20 Leaders\u2019 Statement, Extraordinary G20 Leaders\u2019 Summit Statement on COVID-19]. Retrieved on 5 April 2020.</ref>\n*On '''27 March''' the [[Reserve Bank of India]] (RBI) Governor [[Shaktikanta Das]] made a number of announcements including EMIs being put on hold for three months and reducing [[Repo Rate|repo rates]]. Other measures introduced will make available a total {{INRConvert|374000|c|lk=on|year=2020}} to the country's financial system.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/rbi-joins-coronavirus-fight-rolls-out-big-bang-rate-move/articleshow/74840568.cms|title=RBI joins coronavirus fight with big-bang rate move, EMIs put on hold|date=27 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-27|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Government of Delhi|Delhi government]] announced that from the 28th they will be providing free food to 400,000 every day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/latest/trends/4-lakh-people-to-get-free-food-in-delhi-coronavirus-treatment-capacity-to-be-raised-to-1000-patients-per-day/story/399405.html|title=4 lakh people to get free food in Delhi, coronavirus treatment capacity to be raised to 1,000 patients per day|last=|first=|date=27 March 2020|website=Business Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Over 500 hunger relief centres have been set by the Delhi government.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/delhi/govt-to-give-2-meals-a-day-to-4-lakh-people-says-kejriwal/articleshow/74855058.cms|title=Delhi lockdown: Over 500 hunger relief centres set up for 4 lakh people|last=Mathur|first=Atul|date=28 March 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n*On '''28 March''' the Prime Minister launched a new fund called [[PM CARES fund]] for combating such situations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/pm-cares-pm-narendra-modi-announces-new-covid-19-fund-gets-rs-25-crore-from-akshay-kumar-2202275|title=PM Modi Announces New COVID-19 Fund, Gets Rs 25 Crore From Akshay Kumar|last=|first=|date=28 March 2020|editor-last=Roy|editor-first=Divyanshu Dutta|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n*On '''30 March''' it was announced that the UP government would transfer {{INRConvert|611|c|lk=on|year=2020}} to 27.15 lakh workers under [[National Rural Employment Guarantee Act, 2005|MNREGA]] scheme.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newsonair.com/Main-News-Details.aspx?title=Uttar-Pradesh-govt-to--transfer-Rs-611-crore-in-accounts-of-27.15-lakh-MNREGA-labourers-today&id=384172|title=Uttar Pradesh govt to transfer Rs 611 crore in accounts of 27.15 lakh MNREGA labourers today|last=|first=|date=30 March 2020|website=News on Air, All India Radio|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n*On '''1 April''' the RBI announced more measures to deal with the economic fallout of COVID-19.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite news|last=Nayak|first=Gayatri|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/rbi-announces-more-measures-to-deal-with-economic-fallout-of-covid-19/articleshow/74926767.cms|title=RBI announces more measures to deal with economic fallout of COVID-19|date=2020-04-01|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> [[Ways and means advances|WMA]] and short-term liquidity has been increased to provide relief to state governments; exporters have also been granted some relief in the form of relaxed repatriation limits.<ref name=\":14\" />\n*On '''2 April''' the [[World Bank]] approved $1 bn emergency financing for India to tackle coronavirus labelled 'India COVID-19 Emergency Response and Health Systems Preparedness Project'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldbank.org/en/news/press-release/2020/04/02/world-bank-fast-tracks-1-billion-covid-19-support-for-india|title=World Bank Fast-Tracks $1 Billion COVID-19 (Coronavirus) Support for India|website=World Bank|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/world-bank-approves-1-bn-emergency-financing-for-india-to-tackle-coronavirus-11585852036102.html|title=World Bank approves $1 bn emergency financing for India to tackle coronavirus|date=2020-04-03|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/indicators/covid-fight-is-a-balancing-act-for-worlds-economies-world-bank-india-chief/articleshow/74964031.cms|title=Covid fight is a balancing act for world's economies: World Bank India Chief|date=2020-04-03|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n*On '''3 April''' the central government released {{INRConvert|17287|c|lk=on|year=2020}} to different states to help combat coronavirus. The [[Ministry of Home Affairs (India)|Ministry of Home Affairs]] approved {{INRConvert|11092|c|lk=on|year=2020}} for states as relief under the State Disaster Risk Management Fund.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/centre-grants-rs-17000cr-to-states-to-tackle-coronavirus-crisis/articleshow/74975956.cms|title=Centre grants Rs 17,000cr to states to tackle coronavirus crisis|last=|first=|date=4 April 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n*On '''6 April''' a 30% salary cut for one year was announced for the President, Vice President, Prime Minister, Governors, Members of Parliament and Ministers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/fighting-covid-19-pm-modi-ministers-mps-to-take-30-salary-cut-for-one-year/article31270019.ece|title=Fighting Covid-19: PM Modi, Ministers, MPs to take 30% salary cut for one year|last=|first=|date=6 April 2020|website=The Hindu @businessline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref name=\":21\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/ordinance-passed-to-cut-salaries-of-mps-ministers-by-30-to-fund-covid-19-battle/story-2x9a6obfOxHc5HQ8rhS7FP.html|title=President, MPs, ministers take a pay cut for 1 year, say it is a message|date=2020-04-06|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> It was also decided to suspend the [[MPLADS]] for two years and transfer the money, about {{INRConvert|7900|c|lk=on|year=2020}}, into the [[Consolidated Fund of India|consolidated fund of India]].<ref name=\":21\" />\n*On '''8 April''' the Department of Expenditure, Finance Ministry, has allowed states net market borrowings of {{INRConvert|320481|c|lk=on|year=2020}} between April to December.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/finance/finance-ministry-allows-states-to-borrow-rs-3-20-lakh-crore-from-market/articleshow/75049770.cms|title=Finance Ministry allows states to borrow Rs 3.20 lakh crore from market|date=2020-04-08|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-09|url-status=live|agency=PTI}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/economy-finance/india-borrowing-plan-states-allowed-to-borrow-rs-32-lakh-crore-in-april-december|title=States Allowed To Borrow Rs 3.2 Lakh Crore in April-December|last=Ohri|first=Nikunj|date=8 April 2020|website=BloombergQuint|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> {{INRConvert|3000|c|lk=on|year=2020}} of funds under the [[Pradhan Mantri Garib Kalyan Yojana|PM Garib Kalyan Yojana]] have been given to over 20 million workers engaged in construction work by the various states and UTs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/coronavirus-lockdown-home-ministry-says-states-offer-rs-3-000-crore-funds-to-more-than-2-crore-const-2208530|title=Rs 3,000 Crore Given To 2 Crore Construction Workers By States: Centre|date=8 April 2020|website=NDTV|others=PTI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/productline/building-materials/rs-3000-crore-given-to-2-crore-registered-construction-workers-mha/articleshow/75060935.cms?from=mdr|title=Rs 3000 crore given to 2 crore registered construction workers: MHA|date=2020-04-09|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-09|url-status=live|agency=ANI}}</ref> To provide relief to tax payers amid the covid-19 crisis, the government will release {{INRConvert|18000|c|lk=on|year=2020}}.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Aulakh|first=Gulveen|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/wealth/personal-finance-news/govt-to-immediately-issue-rs-18000-crore-as-pending-tax-refunds-to-individuals-businesses/articleshow/75050023.cms|title=Govt to immediately issue Rs 18,000 crore as pending tax refunds to individuals, businesses|date=2020-04-08|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n*On '''10 April''' the [[Asian Development Bank]] assured India of {{INRConvert|15800|c|lk=on|year=2020}} assistance in the covid-19 outbreak fight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/covid-19-adb-assures-2-2-billion-package-for-india-11586496803375.html|title=Covid-19: ADB assures $2.2 billion package for India|last=Mishra|first=Asit Ranjan|date=2020-04-10|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n* On '''14 April''' at 10am the Prime Minister made a public speech in which he announced the extension of the nationwide lockdown, as well as a calibrated reopening. \"From the economy's point of view, the lockdown undoubtedly looks costly right now, but compared to the lives of Indian citizens, it is nothing\" ''(translation, original in Hindi).''<ref name=\":27\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/india/news/while-extending-indias-lockdown-modi-hinted-at-a-calibrated-re-opening-of-economy-say-experts/articleshow/75135600.cms|title=While extending India's lockdown Modi hinted at a calibrated re-opening of economy, say experts|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n*On '''15 April''' as part of the new lockdown 2.0 guidelines, the [[Ministry of Home Affairs (India)|Ministry of Home Affairs]] announced, among other things, that all agricultural and horticultural activities will remain fully functional.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.business-standard.com/multimedia/video-gallery/general/mha-issues-lockdown-2-0-guidelines-agricultural-horticultural-activities-to-remain-functional-102759.htm|title=MHA issues lockdown 2.0 guidelines: Agricultural, horticultural activities to remain functional|date=15 April 2020|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-15|url-status=live}}</ref> Information technology companies can function with 50% staff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/it-companies-allowed-to-function-with-50-staff-during-lockdown-2-0-11586926334442.html|title=IT companies allowed to function with 50% staff during lockdown 2.0|last=Agarwal|first=Nikhil|date=2020-04-15|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The partial lift of restrictions will take place from 20 April.<ref name=\":28\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52290761|title=India to allow farmers back to work amid lockdown|date=2020-04-15|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-16|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n*On '''17 April''', RBI announced more measures to counter the economic impact of the pandemic including {{INRConvert|50000|c|lk=on|year=2020}} special finance to [[National Bank for Agriculture and Rural Development|NABARD]], [[Small Industries Development Bank of India|SIDBI]], and [[National Housing Bank|NHB]].<ref name=\":30\" /> Providing more relief to state governments, WMA limits have been increased by 60 per cent.<ref name=\":30\" />\n\n=== COVID-19 Economic Response Task Force ===\nThe formation of the COVID-19 Economic Response Task Force was announced by Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] on 19 March 2020 during his live address to the nation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/government-forms-covid-19-economic-response-task-force-pm-modi/articleshow/74716284.cms|title=Covid 19 Economic Task Force: Government forms Covid-19 economic response task force, says PM Modi|last=|first=|date=19 March 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ddnews.gov.in/national/covid-19-task-force-deal-economic-challenges|title=COVID-19: Task Force to deal with economic challenges {{!}} DD News|website=ddnews.gov.in|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pm-narendra-modi-forms-economic-response-task-force-calls-for-janata-curfew/articleshow/74715013.cms?from=mdr|title=PM Narendra Modi forms economic response task force, calls for 'Janata Curfew'|date=2020-03-20|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> The task force is led by the finance minister [[Nirmala Sitharaman]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/coronavirus-impact-fm-led-economic-task-force-takes-stock-of-key-ministries/story/398804.html|title=Coronavirus in India: Economic task force yet to be formed; no decision on relief package|last=|first=|date=20 March 2020|website=Business Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref> Though not formally constituted or no official date for relief packages being made, the consultation process with concerned parties has begun immediately.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/politics/policy/coronavirus-crisis-economic-package-to-be-announced-soon-says-sitharaman-11584722101953.html|title=Coronavirus crisis: Economic package to be announced soon, says Sitharaman|date=2020-03-20|website=Livemint|language=en|others=PTI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/health/subramanian-swamy-writes-to-pm-modi-over-covid-19-says-economic-relief-package-crucial/385273/|title=Subramanian Swamy writes to PM Modi over COVID-19, says economic relief package crucial|last=Nair|first=Remya|date=2020-03-21|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> There were concerns as to where will the government find the funds to fight coronavirus and keep the economy alive.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/where-will-modi-govt-get-money-to-fight-coronavirus-563-mn-fund-hopelessly-small/story/398918.html|title=Where will Modi govt find money to fight coronavirus? $563 mn fund hopelessly small|last=Dubey|first=Rajeev|date=23 March 2020|website=Business Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> Experts say the task force will have to look in to [[Non-performing Asset|NPA]] norms, tax payments and income support to those in the unorganised sectors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/coronavirus-impact-fm-led-economic-task-force-takes-stock-of-key-ministries/story/398804.html|title=Coronavirus in India: Economic task force yet to be formed; no decision on relief package|last=|first=|date=20 March 2020|website=Business Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> A direct cash transfer scheme for the most vulnerable is also being considered, as has happened in other countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbctv18.com/economy/coronavirus-task-force-to-meet-this-evening-to-work-on-relief-package-5522241.htm|title=Coronavirus task force to meet this evening to work on relief package|last=|first=|date=20 March 2020|website=CNBCTV18|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> The [[Ministry of Finance (India)|Ministry of Finance]] immediately started consultations with the RBI and ministries to take stock of most affected sectors like aviation, hospitality, and MSMEs.<ref name=\":1\" /> The [[ASSOCHAM|Associated Chambers of Commerce and Industry of India]] (ASSOCHAM), an apex [[Trade associations|trade association]] of [[India]] gave full support to the efforts.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Market|first=Capital|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-cm/assocham-to-share-ground-level-impact-on-coronavirus-with-economic-response-task-force-120032001822_1.html|title=ASSOCHAM To Share Ground Level Impact On Coronavirus With Economic Response Task Force|date=2020-03-20|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> On 24 March the Finance Minister made a number of announcements related to the economy with regard to the impact of COVID-19.<ref name=\":10\" /> On 26 March the Finance Minister announced more economic relief measures for the poor among other announcements.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\n== Economic situation ==\n[[File:Safe Newspaper Vendor - coronavirus.jpg|thumb|A newspaper vendor in [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]] wearing goggles, safety mask and hand gloves.]]\nIn India up to 53% of businesses have specified a certain amount of impact of shutdowns caused due to COVID-19 on operations ([[FICCI]] survey).<ref name=\":4\" /> Various business such as hotels and airlines are cutting salaries and laying off employees.<ref name=\":2\" /> Live events industry has seen an estimated loss of {{INRConvert|3000|c|lk=on|year=2020}}.<ref name=\":2\" /> A number of young startups have been impacted as funding has fallen.<ref name=\":15\" /> A DataLabs report shows a 45% decrease in the total growth-stage funding ([[Series A round]]) as compared to Q4 2019.<ref name=\":16\" /> On 4 April, former [[Reserve Bank of India]] chief [[Raghuram Rajan]] said that the coronavirus pandemic in India may just be the \"greatest emergency since Independence\".<ref name=\":22\" />\n\nNumerous companies are carrying out measures within their companies to ensure that staff anxiety is kept at a minimum. [[Hero MotoCorp|Hero Motocorp]] has been conducting video townhall meetings, [[Tata Group]] has set up a task force to make working from home more effective and the taskforce at [[Siemens]] also reports on the worldwide situation of the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Philip|first=Lijee|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/company/corporate-trends/india-inc-sets-up-task-forces-as-staff-anxiety-rises/articleshow/74853966.cms|title=India Inc sets up task forces as staff anxiety rises due to Covid-19 lockdown|date=2020-03-28|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-28|last2=Vijayraghavan|first2=Kala}}</ref>\n\nNight lights and economic activity are connected. In Delhi, night light [[radiance]] fell 37.2% compared to 1-31 March 2019. This was the biggest fall for any metro in India. Bangalore fell 32% while Mumbai dropped by 29%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/business/night-lights-tell-the-story-of-dimming-economic-activity-across-india|title=Night Lights Tell The Story Of Dimming Economic Activity Across India|last=Nahata|first=Pallavi|date=11 April 2020|website=BloombergQuint|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Agriculture ===\nDue to logistical problems following the lockdown tea estates were unable to harvest the [[First flush tea|first flush]]. The impact of this on the second flush is not known. The entire Darjeeling tea based tea industry will see significant fall in revenue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/agri-business/covid-19-lockdown-may-brew-trouble-for-tea-sector/article31199394.ece|title=Covid-19 lockdown may brew trouble for tea sector|last=Bose|first=Pratim Ranjan|date=29 March 2020|website=The Hindu @businessline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Tea exports could drop up to 8% as a result.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rakshit|first=Avishek|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/indian-tea-exports-may-decline-by-up-to-8-over-covid-19-outbreak-120040700782_1.html|title=Indian tea exports may decline by up to 8% over Covid-19 outbreak|date=2020-04-07|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nFrom 20 April, under the new lockdown guidelines to reopen the economy and relax the lockdown, agricultural businesses such as dairy, tea, coffee and rubber plantations, as well as associated shops and industries, will reopen.<ref name=\":28\" />\n\n=== Manufacturing ===\nMajor companies in India such as [[Larsen & Toubro|Larsen and Toubro]], [[Bharat Forge]], [[UltraTech Cement]], [[Grasim Industries]], the fashion and retail wing of [[Aditya Birla Group]], [[Tata Motors]] and [[Thermax]] have temporarily suspended or significantly reduced operations in a number of manufacturing facilities and factories across the country. Nearly all two-wheeler and four-wheeler companies have put a stop to production till further notice. Many companies have decided to remain closed till at least 31 March such as [[Cummins]] which has temporarily shut its offices across Maharashtra.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/industry/coronavirus-impact-india-inc-slips-into-sleep-mode/1908492/|title=Coronavirus impact: India Inc slips into sleep mode|last=|first=|date=25 March 2020|website=The Financial Express|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> [[Hindustan Unilever]], [[ITC Limited|ITC]] and [[Dabur India Limited|Dabur India]] have shut manufacturing facilities expect for factories producing essentials.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|last=Mudgill|first=Amit|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/how-will-india-lockdown-play-out-for-economy-markets-4-scenarios/articleshow/74804087.cms|title=How will India lockdown play out for economy & markets: 4 scenarios|date=2020-03-25|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> [[Foxconn]] and [[Wistron Corp.|Wistron Corp]], iPhone producers, have suspended production following the 21 days lockdown orders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-25/iphone-makers-suspend-india-production-due-to-lockdown|title=iPhone Makers Suspend India Production Due to Lockdown|last=Wu|first=Debby|date=25 March 2020|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n=== E-commerce ===\nIn the third week of March, [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] announced that it would stop sale of non-essential items in India so that it can focus on essential needs.<ref name=\":8\" /> Amazon has followed the same strategy in Italy and France.<ref name=\":8\" /> On 25 March, [[Walmart]]-owned [[Flipkart]] temporarily suspended some of its services on its e-commerce platform and will only be selling and distributing essentials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gadgets.ndtv.com/internet/news/flipkart-services-suspended-india-coronavirus-lockdown-walmart-2200237|title=Flipkart Suspends Services as India Enters 21-Day Coronavirus Lockdown|last=Sarwar|first=Nadeem|date=25 March 2020|website=NDTV Gadgets 360|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> BigBasket and [[Grofers]] also run restricted services, facing disruptions in services due to the lockdown.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shrivastava|first=Aditi|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/newsbuzz/despite-govt-clearance-ecomm-cos-find-it-difficult-to-deliver-essentials/articleshow/74803036.cms|title=Despite govt clearance, ecomm cos find it difficult to deliver essentials|date=2020-03-25|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-26|last2=Peermohamed|first2=Alnoor}}</ref> [[Delhi Police]] began issuing delivery agents curfew passes to make it easier for them to keep the supply chain open.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/have-issued-passes-e-commerce-websites-delivery-agents-will-be-helped-delhi-police-11585129545453.html|title=Have issued passes, e-commerce websites' delivery agents will be helped: Police|date=2020-03-25|editor-last=Jagannath|editor-first=J.|website=Livemint|language=en|others=IANS|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> E-commerce companies also look for legal clarity related to what are \"essentials\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Peermohamed|first=Alnoor|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/newsbuzz/covid-19-harried-etailers-look-to-deliver-the-goods/articleshow/74820615.cms|title=Covid-19: Amazon, Flipkart, others look to deliver the goods|date=2020-03-26|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n=== Stock markets ===\nOn 23 March 2020''',''' stock markets in India post worst losses in history.<ref name=\":3\" /> [[BSE SENSEX|SENSEX]] fell 4000 points (13.15%) and [[NIFTY 50|NSE NIFTY]] fell 1150 points (12.98%).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/sensex-hits-10-lower-circuit-what-led-to-the-market-meltdown/articleshow/74768152.cms|title=Sensex crashes 4,000 points: What's behind market meltdown|date=2020-03-23|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> However, on 25 March, one day after a complete 21 day lock-down was announced by the Prime Minister, [[SENSEX]] posted its biggest gains in 11 years, adding a value of  {{INRConvert|4.7|lc|lk=on|year=2020}} crore for investors.<ref name=\":11\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/tech/flipkart-to-resume-shipping-and-deliveries-from-later-today-confirms-ceo-2550957.html|title=Flipkart to Resume Shipping and Deliveries from Later Today, Confirms CEO|last=Das|first=Shouvik|date=2020-03-25|website=News18|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> On 8 April, following positive indication from the Wall Street that the pandemic may have reached its peak in the US, the stock markets in India rose steeply once again.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/markets/market-live-markets-sensex-nifty-bse-nse-sgx-nifty-coronavirus-120040900142_1.html|title=MARKET LIVE: Sensex leaps 1,000 pts, Nifty past 9k; auto stocks rally|last=|first=|date=9 April 2020|website=Business Standard|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/stock-market/news/indian-stock-market-sensex-and-nifty-updates-april-9-2020/articleshow/75058871.cms|title=Indian stock market indices rally over 3% amidst positive cues from global markets|last=Yadav|first=Navdeep|date=9 April 2020|website=Business Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n=== Estimate of economic losses ===\nThe Indian economy is expected to lose over {{INRConvert|32000|c|lk=on|year=2020}} every day during the first 21 days of the lockdown, according to [[SME Rating Agency of India|Acuit\u00e9 Ratings]], a RBI approved [[credit rating agency]].<ref name=\":23\" /> [[Barclays]] said the cost of the first 21 days of shutdown as well as the previous two shorter ones will be total to around {{INRConvert|8.5|lc|lk=on|year=2020}}.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":24\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/experts-peg-indias-cost-of-coronavirus-lockdown-at-usd-120-bn/article31160115.ece|title=Experts peg India's cost of coronavirus lockdown at USD 120 bn|last=PTI|date=25 March 2020|website=The Hindu @businessline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> \n\nOn 27 March, [[Moody's Investors Service]] downgraded its estimate of India's GDP growth for 2020 from 5.3% to 2.5%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/coronavirus-moodys-cuts-india-2020-gdp-growth-forecast-to-2-point-5-percent/story/399377.html|title=Coronavirus: Moody's cuts India's 2020 GDP growth forecast to 2.5%|date=27 March 2020|website=Business Today|others=PTI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> [[Fitch Ratings]] revised its estimate for India's growth to 2%. India Ratings & Research also downgraded the FY21 estimate to 3.6%.<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/business/world-bank-sees-fy21-india-growth-at-15-28-slowest-since-economic-reforms-30-years-ago/article31322011.ece|title=World Bank sees FY21 India growth at 1.5-2.8%, slowest since economic reforms 30 years ago|date=2020-04-12|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-13|others=PTI|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> On 12 April 2020, a [[World Bank]] report focusing on South Asia said that India's economy is expected to grow 1.5% to 2.8% for FY21.<ref name=\":25\" /> This will be the lowest growth for India in 30 years.<ref name=\":26\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/covid-19-causes-severe-disruption-to-indian-economy-says-world-bank/articleshow/75104070.cms|title=World Bank sees FY21 India growth at 1.5-2.8%\u2014 slowest since economic reforms three decades ago|last=|first=|date=12 April 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The World Bank report said that the pandemic has \"magnified pre-existing risks to India\u2019s economic outlook\".<ref name=\":25\" />\n\n[[Confederation of Indian Industry]] (CII) has sought an economic [[Stimulus (economics)|fiscal stimulus]] package of 1% of India's GDP amounting to {{INRConvert|2|lc|lk=on|year=2020}}.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/india-inc-seeks-fiscal-stimulus-moratorium-on-debt-repayment-to-mitigate-coronavirus-impact/articleshow/74759967.cms|title=India Inc seeks fiscal stimulus, moratorium on debt repayment to mitigate coronavirus impact|date=2020-03-22|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-23|url-status=live|agency=PTI}}</ref> The fiscal package and fiscal policies approach is being compared to what has happened in other countries such as Germany, Brazil and Japan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewire.in/economy/interview-india-economic-package-coronavirus|title=India Should Have Already Announced an Economic Package for Coronavirus|last=Srivas|first=Anuj|date=22 March 2020|website=The Wire|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> [[Jefferies Group]] said that the government can spend {{INRConvert|1.3|lc|lk=on|year=2020}} to fight the impact of coronavirus.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-govt-can-spend-18-billion-to-fight-virus-impact-analysts-say-11584949476261.html|title=Coronavirus: Govt can spend $18 billion to fight virus impact, analysts say|date=2020-03-23|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg's]] economists say at least {{INRConvert|2.15|lc|lk=on|year=2020}} needs to be spent.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nIt is estimated that the loss to the tourism industry will be {{INRConvert|15000|c|lk=on|year=2020}} for March and April alone. [[Confederation of Indian Industry|CII]], [[ASSOCHAM]] and FAITH estimate that a huge chunk of the workforce involved with tourism in the country faces unemployment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/nirmala-sitharaman-reviews-sectors-that-may-need-intervention/story-KhFNT5NejEDB4F3K8RPM0H.html|title=Nirmala Sitharaman reviews sectors that may need intervention|last=Jayaswal|first=Rajeev|date=2020-03-21|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n== Concerns and commentary ==\n[[Adar Poonawalla]], CEO of [[Serum Institute of India]] said that \"the economic danger of the outbreak was exponentially greater than its health risks,\" as reported in Economic Times.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/healthcare/biotech/healthcare/coronavirus-vaccine-within-a-year-but-it-wont-be-100-effective/articleshow/74704452.cms?from=mdr|title=Coronavirus vaccine within a year but it won't be 100% effective|date=2020-03-20|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> There are concerns as to where will the government find the funds to fight coronavirus and keep the economy alive.<ref name=\":0\" /> [[Subramanian Swamy]] tweeted on 21 March 2020 asking whether declaration of an financial emergency was inevitable (in the light of the situation because of the coronavirus pandemic).<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n=== Supply chains and logistics ===\nFollowing the lockdown certain essential supply chains broke down.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.unifiedinfotech.net/blog/how-covid-19-changed-ecommerce/|title=Pandemic effect: how Covid-19 changed ecommerce and supply chain industry|date=2020-03-23|work=Unified Infotech|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> [[Britannia Industries]], supporting the lockdown, urged the government to ensure inter-state movement of the raw material for the food processing industry was not hampered. The [[Managing director|Managing Director]] of Britannia stated that \"if even one link in the supply chain is broken, the country could run out of stocks of packaged food in the next 7-10 days.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/cons-products/fmcg/lockdown-britannia-urges-govt-to-issue-necessary-permits-to-people-in-food-processing-supply-chain/articleshow/74825647.cms|title=Lockdown: Britannia urges govt to issue necessary permits to people in food processing supply chain|date=2020-03-26|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Although inter-state travel has been banned, it doesn't apply to essentials, and in places like [[Maharashtra]] the state police is yet to streamline the process, causing a disruption to supply chains.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/coronavirus-outbreak-in-maharashtra-police-disrupting-farm-produce-supply-chains-impairs-farmers-lack-of-labour-stalls-harvest-8193061.html|title=Coronavirus Outbreak: In Maharashtra, police disrupting farm produce supply chains impairs farmers, lack of labour stalls harvest|last=MN|first=Parth|date=26 March 2020|website=Firstpost|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> Vidya Krishnan writes in [[The Atlantic]] that due to the lockdown even movement of medical goods were affected.<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2020/03/india-coronavirus-covid19-narendra-modi/608896/|title=The Callousness of India's COVID-19 Response|last=Krishnan|first=Vidya|date=2020-03-27|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March the government allowed the movement of all essential as well as non-essential goods across the country during the [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown]].<ref name=\":13\" /> The milk and newspaper supply chains are also allowed to function.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\n=== Salaries ===\nThe Prime Minister on 19 March urged businesses and high income segments of society to take care of the economic needs of all those who provide them services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/|title=Business News Today, Stock Market News, Sensex & Finance News|last=Mishra|first=Asit Ranjan|date=19 March 2020|website=Livemint|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> During the live telecast he also appealed to families to not cut the pay of [[domestic help]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/india/news/modi-appeals-people-to-not-cut-the-pay-of-domestic-help-and-others-who-cant-come-to-work/articleshow/74716721.cms|title=Modi appeals people to not cut the pay of domestic help and others who can't come to work|last=Sindwani|first=Prerna|date=20 March 2020|website=Business Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Following the lockdown, the government circulated advisories<ref>Joint Secretary (20 March 2020) [https://labour.gov.in/sites/default/files/Central_Government_Update.pdf Advisory]. Ministry of Labour and Employment, Government of India. Retrieved on 4 April 2020.</ref> and directives ordering companies to keep paying employees among other things.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/company/corporate-trends/how-do-we-keep-paying-wages-wonders-stricken-industry/articleshow/74940685.cms|title=How do we keep paying wages, wonders stricken industry|date=2020-04-02|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/money/unable-to-join-office-ministry-of-labour-and-employment-issues-advisory-to-employers-amidst-coronavirus-crisis/1906909/|title=Concerned about pay cut, losing job amid Coronavirus crisis? Labour Ministry issues advisory to employers|date=2020-03-23|website=The Financial Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The [[Ministry of Finance (India)|Ministry of Finance]] issued an Office Memorandum on 23 March 2020:<ref name=\":18\" /><ref>Additional Secretary to the Govt of India, Department of Expenditure (23 March 2020) [https://doe.gov.in/sites/default/files/Payment%20of%20Wages%20to%20Outsourced_Contractual%20Staff%20-%20COVID%2019.pdf Office Memorandum]. Ministry of Finance. Retrieved on 4 April 2020.</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=[...] wherever such contractual, the casual and outsourced staff of Ministries/Departments and other organization of Government of India is required to stay at home in view of lockdown order regarding COVID-19 prevention [...] they shall be treated as \"on duty\" during such period of absence and necessary pay/wages would be paid accordingly. [...] <br/>These instructions shall apply until April 30, 2020.|author=Addt Sect, Dept of Expenditure, Ministry of Finance|title=|source=}}\n\nA few days later worries grew as to how wages could continue being paid and if the directive was legal or not.<ref name=\":17\" /> There were also concerns raised by migrant workers regarding implementation of the orders as many daily-wagers have no records of being sacked or salaries being paid or deducted; the concerns also expand to uncertainty in the government's ability to enforce minimum wages under a lockdown when it couldn't even do so during normal times.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/migrants-question-implementation-of-govt-advisory-on-protecting-wages-jobs/story-bSJcx1l7ODCA1qgUBnG6qJ.html|title=Migrants question implementation advisory on protecting wages, jobs|last=Dey|first=Abhishek|date=2020-04-01|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Migrant workers and labour force ===\nDue to the lockdown, there suddenly was no work for many daily workers (the urban poor and migrant labourers). At the same time the lockdown restrictions put a stop on the movement of buses and trains. Large numbers of migrant workers ended up walking back to there villages, some journeys hundreds of kilometers long. Commentators commented on how the whole purpose of social distancing was defeated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/global-economics/india-s-government-should-have-expected-coronavirus-migration|title=Coronavirus Exposes India's Official Callousness|last=Sharma|first=Mihir|date=1 April 2020|website=BloombergQuint|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref name=\":19\" />\n\nSoon after a central government directive in late March, state governments set up 21,000 camps to house over 660,000 migrants and stop the exodus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/more-than-21000-camps-set-up-for-over-660000-migrants-state-governments/articleshow/74920798.cms|title=More than 21,000 camps set up for over 6,60,000 migrants: State governments|date=2020-04-01|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Delhi government is providing free food to 400,000 people every day.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/coronavirus-delhi-to-feed-4-lakh-people-from-tomorrow-ready-for-even-1000-cases-a-day-says-kejriwal/article31180118.ece|title=Coronavirus {{!}} Delhi govt to feed 4 lakh people from tomorrow; ready for even 1,000 cases a day, says Kejriwal|date=2020-03-27|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-03|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> Over 500 hunger relief centres have been set by the Delhi government.<ref name=\":20\" />\n\nBy 5 April, 75,00,000 people were being provided food across the country in government and NGO food camps.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/nation/over-75-lakh-being-fed-at-food-camps-mha-66223|title=Over 75 lakh being fed at food camps: MHA|date=6 April 2020|work=The Tribune|access-date=12 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Lockdown extension ===\nOn 8 April 2020, the managing director of [[Bajaj Auto]], [[Rajiv Bajaj]], wrote in an opinion piece in the [[The Economic Times|Economic Times]] that the \"lockdown makes India weak rather than stronger in combating the epidemic,\" and that the current \"arbitrary\" lockdown was totally unsustainable and a \"recalibration\" is needed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/business/coronavirus-lockdown-makes-india-weak-rather-than-stronger-rajiv-bajaj-writes-in-et|title=Coronavirus Lockdown Makes India Weak Rather Than Stronger, Rajiv Bajaj Writes In ET|website=BloombergQuint|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/view-must-sell-ourselves-out-of-this-crisis/articleshow/75038503.cms|title=India may have to sell itself out of this crisis, says Rajiv Bajaj|date=2020-04-08|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> Rajiv Bajaj writes that \"India may have to sell itself out of the coronavirus crisis\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://auto.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/industry/india-may-have-to-sell-itself-out-of-this-crisis-says-rajiv-bajaj/75058899|title=India may have to sell itself out of this crisis, says Rajiv Bajaj - ET Auto|last=|first=|date=9 April 2020|website=ETAuto|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the extension of the lockdown on 14 April, members of the opposition said that there was no mention of a financial package or any steps whatsoever to revive the economy.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/congress-says-pm-modis-address-hollow-no-mention-of-financial-package/article31336629.ece|title=Congress says PM Modi\u2019s address 'hollow', no mention of financial package|date=2020-04-14|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-14|url-status=live|agency=PTI|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> Modi however did talk about a re-calibrated opening of the economy.<ref name=\":27\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* Suvojit Chattopadhyay (27 March 2020). [https://qz.com/india/1826705/modis-coronavirus-relief-package-will-work-if-distributed-fairly/ India\u2019s $23 billion coronavirus relief package will help only if it reaches those in need]. [[Quartz India]]\n* Soutik Biswas (30 March 2020). [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52086274 Coronavirus: India's pandemic lockdown turns into a human tragedy]. BBC\n* Arunoday Mukharji (3 April 2020). [https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52117704 Coronavirus: India's bailout may not be enough to save economy]. BBC\n*Pallavi Nahata (13 April 2020). [https://www.bloombergquint.com/business/in-charts-the-emerging-economic-impact-of-a-nationwide-lockdown In Charts: The Emerging Economic Impact Of A Nationwide Lockdown]. [[BloombergQuint]] {{Locked content}} \n*Shivani Sharma, Mohsin Shaikh \u00a0(17 April 2020). [https://www.businesstoday.in/current/graphics/infographic-coronavirus-india-economy/story/401325.html Infographic: How coronavirus has hurt Indian economy]. [[Business Today (India)|Business Today<br />]]\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "103.61.113.112", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_impact_of_the_2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic_in_India"}
